definitions: A prefix of obscure meaning, originally used with verbs, adverbs, adjectives, nouns, and pronouns. In the Middle English period, it was little employed except with verbs, being chiefly used with past participles, though occasionally with the infinitive Ycleped, or yclept, is perhaps the only word not entirely obsolete which shows this use. That no wight mighte it see neither yheere. Chaucer. Neither to ben yburied nor ybrent. Chaucer.
A prefix meaning about, around; -- used in words derived from the Latin.
A prefix in words from the Greek, denoting up, upward, throughout, backward, back, again, anew.
See Anti-, prefix.
A suffix sometimes marking the agent for action; as, merchant, covenant, servant, pleasant, etc. Cf. -ent.
A combining form of azote;
Applied loosely to compounds having nitrogen variously combined, as in cyanides, nitrates, etc.
Now especially applied to compounds containing a two atom nitrogen group uniting two hydrocarbon radicals, as in azobenzene, azobenzoic, etc. These compounds furnish many artificial dyes. See Diazo-.
A Latin preposition, sometimes used as a prefix in English words, and signifying on this side.

A prefix from the Latin preposition cum, signifying with, together, in conjunction, very, etc. It is used in the form com- before b, m, p, and sometimes f, and by assimilation becomes col- before l, cor- before r, and con- before any consonant except b, h, l, m, p, r, and w. Before a vowel com- becomes co-; also before h, w, and sometimes before other consonants.
A prefix signifying with, together, etc. See Com-.
A prefix denoting through; also, between, apart, asunder, across. Before a vowel dia- becomes di-; as, diactinic; dielectric, etc.

A prefix from the Latin, whence F. dés, or sometimes dé-, dis-. The Latin dis- appears as di- before b, d, g, l, m, n, r, v, becomes dif- before f, and either dis- or di- before j. It is from the same root as bis twice, and duo, E. two. See Two, and cf. Bi-, Di-, Dia-. Dis- denotes separation, a parting from, as in distribute, disconnect; hence it often has the force of a privative and negative, as in disarm, disoblige, disagree. Also intensive, as in dissever.
A prefix from Gr. Di-.
An inseparable prefix, fr. the Greek ill, bad, hard, difficult, and the like; cf. the prefixes, Skr. dus-, Goth. tuz-, OHG. zur-, G. zer-, AS. to-, Icel. tor-, Ir. do-.
A combining form signifying without, outside, external.
Originally, the highest note in the scale of Guido; hence, proverbially, any extravagant saying. "Why, this is above E-la!" Beau. & Fl.
A prefix signifying within. See Ento-.
An adjective suffix signifying action or being; as, corrodent, excellent, emergent, continent, quiescent. See -ant.
A prefix, meaning upon, beside, among, on the outside, above, over. It becomes ep- before a vowel, as in epoch, and eph- before a Greek aspirate, as in ephemeral.

A prefix to verbs, having usually the force of a negative or privative. It often implies also loss, detriment, or destruction, and sometimes it is intensive, meaning utterly, quite thoroughly, as in forbathe.
A prefix or combining form, used to denote six, sixth, etc.; as, hexatomic, hexabasic.
A prexif used in anatomy, and generally denoting connection with the hyoid bone or arch; as, hyoglossal, hyomandibular, hyomental, etc.
See Iodo-.
A prefix or combining form, indicating identity, or equality; the same numerical value; as in isopod, isomorphous, isochromatic. Specif.:
. A prefix in composition denoting ill,or evil, F. male, adv., fr. malus, bad, ill. In some words it has the form male-, as in malediction, malevolent. See Malice.
Combining forms signifying: (a) Great, extended, powerful; as, megascope, megacosm. (b) (Metric System, Elec., Mech., etc.)
A million times, a million of; as, megameter, a million meters; megafarad, a million farads; megohm, a million ohms.
See Meso-.
A prefix used adjectively and adverbially in the sense of amiss, wrong, ill, wrongly, unsuitably; as, misdeed, mislead, mischief, miscreant.
Same as Mono-.
A combining form of Gr. muscle; as, myograph, myochrome.

A prefix meaning new, recent, late; and in chemistry designating specifically that variety of metameric hydrocarbons which, when the name was applied, had been recently classified, and in which at least one carbon atom in connected directly with four other carbon atoms; -- contrasted with normal and iso-; as, neopentane; the neoparaffins. Also used adjectively.
A prefix used in the sense of not; un-; in-; as in nonattention, or non-attention, nonconformity, nonmetallic, nonsuit.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the shoulder or the scapula.
A combining form denoting relation to, or situation near or in, the ear.
A prefix, also used adjectively, designating:
A compound containing oxygen.
A compound containing the hydroxyl group, more properly designated by hydroxy-. See Hydroxy-. Oxy acid. See Oxyacid (below).
Combining forms signifying all, every; as, panorama, pantheism, pantagraph, pantograph. Pan- becomes pam- before b or p, as pamprodactylous.

A prefix used to signify through, throughout, by, for, or as an intensive as perhaps, by hap or chance; perennial, that lasts throughout the year; perforce, through or by force; perfoliate, perforate; perspicuous, evident throughout or very evident; perplex, literally, to entangle very much.

Originally, denoting that the element to the name of which it is prefixed in the respective compounds exercised its highest valence; now, only that the element has a higher valence than in other similar compounds; thus, barium peroxide is the highest oxide of barium; while nitrogen and manganese peroxides, so-called, are not the highest oxides of those elements.

A prefix signifying before, in front, forth, for, in behalf of, in place of, according to; as, propose, to place before; proceed, to go before or forward; project, to throw forward; prologue, part spoken before (the main piece); propel, prognathous; provide, to look out for; pronoun, a word instead of a noun; proconsul, a person acting in place of a consul; proportion, arrangement according to parts.
A combining form meaning six; as, sexdigitism; sexennial.

A prefix signifying under, below, beneath, and hence often, in an inferior position or degree, in an imperfect or partial state, as in subscribe, substruct, subserve, subject, subordinate, subacid, subastringent, subgranular, suborn. Sub- in Latin compounds often becomes sum- before m, sur before r, and regularly becomes suc-, suf- , sug-, and sup- before c, f, g, and p respectively. Before c, p, and t it sometimes takes form sus- (by the dropping of b from a collateral form, subs-).

A prefix denoting that the ingredient (of a compound) signified by the term to which it is prefixed,is present in only a small proportion, or less than the normal amount; as, subsulphide, suboxide, etc. Prefixed to the name of a salt it is equivalent to basic; as, subacetate or basic acetate. [Obsoles.]
A form of the prefix Sub-.
A prefix signifying over, above, beyond, upon.
See Syn-.
A prefix meaning with, along with, together, at the same time. Syn- becomes sym- before p, b, and m, and syl- before l.
A combining form from L. ter signifying three times, thrice. See Tri-, 2.
A prefix meaning three, thrice, threefold; as in tricolored, tridentate.
A prefix (also used adjectively) denoting three proportional or combining part, or the third degree of that to the name of which it is prefixed; as in trisulphide, trioxide, trichloride.
A prefix signifying one, once; as in uniaxial, unicellular.
A combining form fr. Gr. o'y^ron, urine.
A combining form from Gr. o'yra`, the tail, the caudal extremity.
A combining form from Gr. zwo^,n an animal, as in zoögenic, zoölogy, etc.
Combining forms of the Greek word for gland; -- used in words relating to the structure, diseases, etc., of the glands.
The combining form of the Greek word meaning air.

A Latin preposition and prefix; akin to Gr. anti, Goth. and-, anda- (only in comp.), AS. and-, ond-, (only in comp.: cf. Answer, Along), G. ant-, ent- (in comp.). The Latin ante is generally used in the sense of before, in regard to position, order, or time, and the Gr. opposite, or in the place of.
A prefix signifying chief, as in archbuilder, archfiend.
A combining form, with the meaning of self, one's self, one's own, itself, its own.

A combining form, especially in anatomical and botanical words, to indicate the base or position at or near a base; forming a base; as, basibranchials, the most ventral of the cartilages or bones of the branchial arches; basicranial, situated at the base of the cranium; basifacial, basitemporal, etc.
A prefix, from Gr. de`ka, signifying ten; specifically (Metric System), a prefix signifying the weight or measure that is ten times the principal unit.
A prefix signifying ten. See Deca-.
A prefix, signifying half.
See Ect-.
A combining form signifying within; as, endocarp, endogen, endocuneiform, endaspidean.
A combining form signifying within; as, entoblast.
A prefix, meaning equally; as, equidistant; equiangular.
A combining form indicating fluorine as an ingredient; as in fluosilicate, fluobenzene.
A passing without notice; intentional neglect; thrusting away; a shifting off; adieu; as, to give a proposal the go-by. Some songs to which we have given the go-by. Prof. Wilson.
A sunk fence; a fence, wall, or ditch, not visible till one is close upon it. [Written also haw-haw.]
Same as Hæma-.
A prefix signifying half.
Same as Hæma-, Hæmo-.
A combining form fr. Gr. "o`los whole.
A combining form from Gr. "omo`s, one and the same, common, joint.
. See under Hydro-.
A prefix signifying a less quantity, or a low state or degree, of that denoted by the word with which it is joined, or position under or beneath.

A prefix denoting that the element to the name of which it is prefixed enters with a low valence, or in a low state of oxidization, usually the lowest, into the compounds indicated; as, hyposulphurous acid.
. A combining form from the Gr. idea.
. A combining form from the Greek private, personal, peculiar, distinct.
A combining form used in anatomy to denote connection with, or relation to, the ilium; as, ilio-femoral, ilio-lumbar, ilio-psoas, etc.
A prefix signifying Indian (i. e., East Indian); of or pertaining of India.
A prefix, or combining from, indicating iodine as an ingredient; as, iodoform.
A combining form used to signify thousand in forming the names of units of measurement; as, kilogram, kilometer, kilowatt, etc.
. Same as Leuco-.
A prefix from L. laevus, meaning:
Pertaining to, or toward, the left; as, levorotatory.
. See Mal-.
A combining form denoting in the middle, intermediate; specif. (Chem.), denoting a type of hydrocarbons which are regarded as methenyl derivatives. Also used adjectively.
A prefix meaning between, with, after, behind, over, about, reversely; as, metachronism, the error of placing after the correct time; metaphor, lit., a carrying over; metathesis, a placing reversely.
Other; duplicate, corresponding to; resembling; hence, metameric; as, meta-arabinic, metaldehyde.

A prefix signifying one, single, alone; as, monocarp, monopoly; (Chem.) indicating that a compound contains one atom, radical, or group of that to the name of which it is united; as, monoxide, monosulphide, monatomic, etc.
See Multi-.
A combining form denoting pertaining to, or connected with, the nose; as, nasofrontal.
A prefix meaning eight. See Octo-.
A combining form meaning eight; as in octodecimal, octodecimal, octolocular.
A combining form denoting all, every, everywhere; as in omnipotent, all-powerful; omnipresent.
A prefix signifying alongside of, beside, beyond, against, amiss; as parable, literally, a placing beside; paradox, that which is contrary to opinion; parachronism.

A prefix denoting: (a) Likeness, similarity, or connection, or that the substance resembles, but is distinct from, that to the name of which it is prefixed; as paraldehyde, paraconine, etc.; also, an isomeric modification. (b) Specifically: (Organ. Chem.) That two groups or radicals substituted in the benzene nucleus are opposite, or in the respective positions 1 and 4; 2 and 5; or 3 and 6, as paraxylene; paroxybenzoic acid. Cf. Ortho-, and Meta-. Also used adjectively.
A combining form signifying equal; as, paridigitate, paripinnate.
Combining forms from L. pes, pedis, foot, as pedipalp, pedireme, pedometer.

A prefix used to signify around, by, near, over, beyond, or to give an intensive sense; as, perimeter, the measure around; perigee, point near the earth; periergy, work beyond what is needed; perispherical, quite spherical.
A combining form or prefix from Gr. poy`s, podo`s, foot; as, podocarp, podocephalous, podology.
A prefix signifying behind, back, after; as, postcommissure, postdot, postscript.
A prefix. See Pre-.

Combining forms designating fire or heat; specifically (Chem.), used to imply an actual or theoretical derivative by the action of heat; as in pyrophosphoric, pyrosulphuric, pyrotartaric, pyrotungstic, etc.
A prefix signifying half, and sometimes partly or imperfectly; as, semiannual, half yearly; semitransparent, imperfectly transparent.

A prefix used before father, mother, brother, sister, son, daughter, child, etc., to indicate that the person thus spoken of is not a blood relative, but is a relative by the marriage of a parent; as, a stepmother to X is the wife of the father of X, married by him after the death of the mother of X. See Stepchild, Stepdaughter, Stepson, etc.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting the presence of sulphur. See Sulpho-.
Bustle; stir; commotion; ado. [Colloq.]
A combining form from Gr. xy`lon wood; as in xylogen, xylograph.
A prefix in words of Greek origin, signifying both, of both kinds, on both sides, about, around.
A prefix, or combining form, in numerous compounds, usually relating to seed or blood vessels, or to something contained in, or covered by, a vessel.

A combining form meaning the same as English; or English and, or English conjoined with; as, Anglo-Turkish treaty, Anglo-German, Anglo-Irish. Anglo-American, . Of or pertaining to the English and Americans, or to the descendants of Englishmen in America.  -- n. A descendant from English ancestors born in America, or the United States. Anglo-Danish, a. Of or pertaining to the English and Danes, or to the Danes who settled in England. Anglo-Indian, a. Of or pertaining to the English in India, or to the English and East Indian peoples or languages.  -- n. One of the Anglo-Indian race born or resident in the East Indies. Anglo-Norman, a. Of or pertaining to the English and Normans, or to the Normans who settled in England.  -- n. One of the English Normans, or the Normans who conquered England. Anglo-Saxon. See Anglo-Saxon in the Vocabulary.
A prefix signifying chief, arch; as, architect, archiepiscopal. In Biol. and Anat. it usually means primitive, original, ancestral; as, archipterygium, the primitive fin or wing.
The combining form of the Greek word 'a`stron, meaning star.
The whole; all that is to be. [Poetic] Shak.
Private end or interest; secret purpose; selfish advantage. [Written also bye-end.] "Profit or some other by-end." L'Estrange.

A local or subordinate law; a private law or regulation made by a corporation for its own government. There was likewise a law to restrain the by-laws, or ordinances of corporations. Bacon. The law or institution; to which are added two by-laws, as a comment upon the general law. Addison.

A law that is less important than a general law or constitutional provision, and subsidiary to it; a rule relating to a matter of detail; as, civic societies often adopt a constitution and by-laws for the government of their members. In this sense the word has probably been influenced by by, meaning secondary or aside.
A combining form meaning circular, of a circle or wheel.

A prefix which formerly properly indicated the second in a regular series of compound in the series, and not to its composition, but which is now generally employed in the same sense as bi- or di-, although little used.

A combining form (also used adjectively), meaning pertaining to, or derived from, a series of compounds containing a radical of two nitrogen atoms, united usually to an aromatic radical; as, diazo- benzene, C6H5.N2.OH.
General manager; factotum. Under him, Dunstan was the do-all at court, being the king's treasurer, councilor, chancellor, confessor, all things. Fuller.
A prefix signifying between, among, part.

A Latin preposition, denoting beyond, outside of; -- often used in composition as a prefix signifying outside of, beyond, besides, or in addition to what is denoted by the word to which it is prefixed.
A combining form indicating ferric iron as an ingredient; as, ferricyanide.
A prefix, or combining form, indicating ferrous iron as an ingredient; as, ferrocyanide.
General composition or structure; manner in which the parts of a thing are combined; make-up; style of dress, etc. [Colloq.] H. Kingsley.
A sluice in embankments against the sea, for letting out the land waters, when the tide is out. [Written also gowt.]
Combining forms indicating relation or resemblance to blood, association with blood; as, hæmapod, hæmatogenesis, hæmoscope.
See Hæma-.
A combining form from Gr. "h`lios the sun.
A combining form from Gr. Hydra).
A combining form of hydrogen, indicating hydrogen as an ingredient, as hydrochloric; or a reduction product obtained by hydrogen, as hydroquinone.
A prefix signifying over, above; as, hyperphysical, hyperthyrion; also, above measure, abnormally great, excessive; as, hyperæmia, hyperbola, hypercritical, hypersecretion.
A prefix equivalent to super- or per-; as hyperoxide, or peroxide. [Obs.] See Per-.
. A prefix. See Levo.
Abatement; also, cessation; as, it blew a gale for three days without any let-up. [Colloq.]

A combining form signifying white, colorless; specif. (Chem.), denoting an extensive series of colorless organic compounds, obtained by reduction from certain other colored compounds; as, leucaniline, leucaurin, etc.
A combining form signifying orange yellow or brownish yellow.
A combining form signifying long, large, great; as macrodiagonal, macrospore.
A combining form signifying:
Small, little, trivial, slight; as, microcosm, microscope.
A prefix denoting a thousandth part of; as, millimeter, milligram, milliampère.
A prefix signifying much or many; several; more than one; as, multiaxial, multocular.
A prefix, esp. in the metric system, indicating ten thousand, ten thousand times; as, myriameter.
A combining denoting a nerve, of or pertaining to a nerve or the nervous system.
A combining form or an adjective denoting the presence of niter.

A combining form (used also adjectively) designating certain compounds of nitrogen or of its acids, as nitrohydrochloric, nitrocalcite; also, designating the group or radical NO2, or its compounds, as nitrobenzene. Nitro group, the radical NO2; -- called also nitroxyl.
A combining form from L. oculus the eye.
A combining form from Gr. few, little, small.
A combining form signifying straight, right, upright, correct, regular; as, orthodromy, orthodiagonal, orthodox, orthographic.
A combining form (also used adjectively), designating:

Connection with, or affinity to, one variety of isomerism, characteristic of the benzene compounds; -- contrasted with meta- or para-; as, the ortho position; hence, designating any substance showing such isomerism; as, an ortho compound.
A combining form of Gr. a bone.
A combining form meaning thick; as, pachyderm, pachydactyl.
A combining form meaning old, ancient; as, palearctic, paleontology, paleothere, paleography. [Written also palæo-.]
See Pan-.
See Pan-.
A combining form denoting five; as, pentacapsular; pentagon.
Denoting the degree of five, either as regards quality, property, or composition; as, pentasulphide; pentoxide, etc. Also used adjectively.
A combining form from Gr. rock, stone; as, petrology, petroglyphic.
A combining form from Gr. fi`los loving, fond of, attached to; as, philosophy, philotechnic.
A combining form from Gr. sound, tone; as, phonograph, phonology.
A combining form from Gr. fw^s, fwto`s, light; as, photography, phototype, photometer.
A combining form from Gr. fyto`n a plant; as, phytochemistry, phytography.
See Plani-.
A combining form from Gr. platy`s broad, wide, flat; as, platypus, platycephalous.
A combining form from L. plus, pluris, more, many; as pluriliteral.
A combining form prefix signifying first, primary, primordial; as, protomartyr, the first martyr; protomorphic, primitive in form; protoplast, a primordial organism; prototype, protozoan.
Denoting the first or lowest of a series, or the one having the smallest amount of the element to the name of which it is prefixed; as protoxide, protochloride, etc.
Sometimes used as equivalent to mono-, as indicating that the compound has but one atom of the element to the name of which it is prefixed. Also used adjectively.
A combining form indicating connection with, or relation to, a radius or ray; specifically (Anat.), with the radius of the forearm; as, radio-ulnar, radiomuscular, radiocarpal.
A combining form signifying straight; as, rectilineal, having straight lines; rectinerved.
A combining form indicating connection with, or relation to, the rectum; as, recto-vesical.
A combining form from Greek the nose, as in rhinolith, rhinology.
A prefix (also used adjectively) signifying rose-red; specifically used to designate certain rose-red compounds (called roseo-cobaltic compounds) of cobalt with ammonia. Cf. Luteo-.
A combining form denoting connection with, or relation to, the sacrum, as in sacro-coccyageal, sacro-iliac, sacrosciatic.
A combining form meaning seven; as, septifolious, seven-leaved; septi-lateral, seven-sided.
A contest in boxing, in an argument, or the like. [Colloq.] Halliwell.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting the presence of sodium or one of its compounds.
The gamut, or musical scale. See Tonic sol-fa, under Tonic, n.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the styloid process of the temporal bone; as, stylohyal, stylomastoid, stylomaxillary.

A prefix signifying above, over, beyond, and hence often denoting in a superior position, in excess, over and above, in addition, exceedingly; as in superimpose, supersede, supernatural, superabundance.

A prefix formerly much used to denote that the ingredient to the name of which it was prefixed was present in a large, or unusually large, proportion as compared with the other ingredients; as in calcium superphosphate. It has been superseded by per-, bi-, di-, acid, etc. (as peroxide, bicarbonate, disulphide, and acid sulphate), which retain the old meanings of super-, but with sharper definition. Cf. Acid, a., Bi-, Di-, and Per-.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the tarsus; as, tarsometatarsus.
A tittering laugh; a titter. "'Te-hee,' quoth she." Chaucer.
A combining form or prefix signifying four, as in tetrabasic, tetrapetalous.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting four proportional or combining parts of the substance or ingredient denoted by the term to which it is prefixed, as in tetra-chloride, tetroxide.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the thyroid body or the thyroid cartilage; as, thyrohyal.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the tibia; as, tibiotarsus, tibiofibular.
The spotted sandpiper; -- called also teeter-tail. See under Sandpiper.
The present day. today. On to-day Is worth for me a thousand yesterdays. Longfellow.
A prefix, signifying over, beyond, through and through, on the other side, as in transalpine, beyond the Alps; transform, to form through and through, that is, anew, transfigure.
Something serving to tie or secure. [Obs.] Latimer.

The higher literary idiom of Chinese, that of the canonical books and of all composition pretending to literary standing. It employs a classical or academic diction, and a more condensed and sententious style than Mandarin, and differs also in the doubling and arrangement of words.
A combining form from zinc; in chemistry, designating zinc as an element of certain double compounds. Also used adjectively.
A combining form (also used adjectively) designating zirconium as an element of certain double compounds; zircono-; as in zircofluoric acid, sodium zircofluoride.
A combining form meaning anterior, front; as, antero-posterior, front and back; antero-lateral, front side, anterior and at the side.
A singular nocturnal quadruped, allied to the lemurs, found in Madagascar (Cheiromys Madagascariensis), remarkable for its long fingers, sharp nails, and rodent-like incisor teeth.
Bow-compasses carrying a drawing pen. See Bow-compass.
A saw with a thin or narrow blade set in a strong frame.
A side or incidental blow; an accidental blow. With their by-blows they did split the very stones in pieces. Bunyan.
An illegitimate child; a bastard. The Aga speedily . . . brought her [his disgraced slave] to court, together with her pretty by-blow, the present Padre Ottomano. Evelyn.
A private lane, or one opening out of the usual road.
A nickname. Camden.
A by-passage, for a pipe, or other channel, to divert circulation from the usual course.
A private room or apartment. "Stand in some by-room" Shak.
A private or selfish view; self-interested aim or purpose. No by-views of his own shall mislead him. Atterbury.
secluded or private walk. He moves afterward in by-walks. Dryden.
The outlet from a dam or reservoir; also, a cut to divert the flow of water.
A secret or side stroke, as of raillery or sarcasm. Milton.
A prefix denoting that chlorine is an ingredient in the substance named.
A Latin preposition, used as a prefix in many English words, and signifying around or about.
A joint ally. Kent.
A companion. Shak.
That which cuts off or shortens, as a nearer passage or road.

The valve gearing or mechanism by which steam is cut off from entering the cylinder of a steam engine after a definite point in a stroke, so as to allow the remainder of the stroke to be made by the expansive force of the steam already let in. See Expansion gear, under Expansion.
Any device for stopping or changing a current, as of grain or water in a spout.
A net for catching small birds.
A prefix, from L. dexter, meaning, pertaining to, or toward, the right; (Chem. & Opt.)
having the property of turning the plane of polarized light to the right; as, dextrotartaric acid.
A male fox. See the Note under Dog, n.,
Sir W. Scott.
The Arctic or blue fox; -- a name also applied to species of the genus Cynalopex.
A cup used for holding an egg, at table.
An offering to a church in fulfillment of a vow.

A Chinese gambling game in which coins or other small objects are placed upon a table, usually under a cup, and the players bet as to what remainder will be left when the sum of the counters is divided by four.
A game with playing cards in which the cards are played in sequences upon the table, the one who first gets rid of his cards being the winner.
A combining form signifying relating to the forehead or the frontal bone; as, fronto-parietal, relating to the frontal and the parietal bones; fronto-nasal, etc.
A combining form from the Gr. gastrocolic, gastrocele, gastrotomy.
A male cat, esp. an old one. See lst Gib. n. [Obs.] Shak.
Farewell; a form of address used at parting. See the last Note under By, prep. Shak.
A dependent; a hanger-on; -- so called in contempt. B. Jonson.
See Ha-ha.
A combining form signifying other, other than usual, different; as, heteroclite, heterodox, heterogamous.
A spree; a revel. [Low]
The goatsucker.
A device for letting off, releasing, or giving forth, as the warp from the cylinder of a loom.
The formation of football players before the start or a restart of play; hence (Colloq.),
any arrangement of persons (rarely, of things), esp. when having a common purpose or sentiment; as, the line-up at a ticket- office window; the line-up of political factions.
A noun suffix, commonly having a diminutive or a depreciatory force; as in duck-ling, dosling, hireling, fosterling, firstling, underling.
. An adverbial suffix; as, darkling, flatling.

The way in which the parts of anything are put together; often, the way in which an actor is dressed, painted, etc., in personating a character. The unthinking masses are necessarily teleological in their mental make-up. L. F. Ward.
See Meg-.
Same as Bablh.
. A combining from Gr. nhema, nhematos, a thread.
The union of being and relation as distinguished from, and contrasted with, the ego. See Ego.
A combining form from Gr.
A combining form denoting relation to, or connection with, an organ or organs.
See Paleo-.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate relation to, or connection with, the palate; as in palatolingual.
A combining form from Gr. a leaf; as, phyllopod, phyllotaxy.
Act of picking up, as, in various games, the fielding or hitting of a ball just after it strikes the ground.
That which picks up; specif.: (Elec.)
= Brush b.
One that is picked up, as a meal hastily got up for the occasion, a chance acquaintance, an informal game, etc.
A combining form denoting relation to a side; specif., connection with, or situation in or near, the pleura; as, pleuroperitoneum.
A combining form from Gr. a lung; as, pneumogastric, pneumology.

A Vickers-Maxim one-pounder automatic machine cannon using metallic ammunition fed from a lopped belt attached to the gun; -- popularly so called from its peculiar drumming sound in action. Sometimes, any of other similar automatic cannons.
A combining form signifying green; as, praseocobalt, a green variety of cobalt.
A prefix signifying past, by, beyond, more than; as, preter- mission, a permitting to go by; preternatural, beyond or more than is natural. [Written also præter.]

A combining form or prefix signifying false, counterfeit, pretended, spurious; as, pseudo-apostle, a false apostle; pseudo- clergy, false or spurious clergy; pseudo-episcopacy, pseudo-form, pseudo-martyr, pseudo-philosopher. Also used adjectively.
A combining form from Gr. the soul, the mind, the understanding; as, psychology.
A shift for evasion or delay; an evasion; an excuse. L'Estrange.
A combining form meaning four, four times, fourfold; as, quadricapsular, having four capsules.
An eruption of red pimples upon the face, neck, and arms, in early infancy; tooth rash; strophulus. Good.
A name of rust on grain. See Rust.
An instrument used to set or turn the teeth of a saw a little sidewise, that they may make a kerf somewhat wider than the thickness of the blade, to prevent friction; -- called also saw-wrest.
A combining form denoting division or cleavage; as, schizogenesis, reproduction by fission or cell division.
A tern.
Any species of ear-shaped shells of the genus Haliotis. See Abalone.
A globefish.
A pennatula.

A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting that three atoms or equivalents of the substance to the name of which it is prefixed are combined with two of some other element or radical; as, sesquibromide, sesquicarbonate, sesquichloride, sesquioxide.
That which is set off against another thing; an offset. I do not contemplate such a heroine as a set-off to the many sins imputed to me as committed against woman. D. Jerrold.
That which is used to improve the appearance of anything; a decoration; an ornament.
A counterclaim; a cross debt or demand; a distinct claim filed or set up by the defendant against the plaintiff's demand.
Same as Offset, n., 4.
See Offset, 7.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting the presence of silicon or its compounds; as, silicobenzoic, silicofluoride, etc.
A kind of overcoat worn upon the shoulders in the manner of a cloak. [Scot.]
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the sphenoid bone; as in sphenomaxillary, sphenopalatine.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting relation to, or connection with, tin, or including tin as an ingredient.
A combining form meaning solid, hard, firm, as in stereo- chemistry, stereography.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the sternum; as, sternocostal, sternoscapular.
A prefix (also used adjectively) designating sulphur as an ingredient in certain compounds. Cf. Thio-.
The lowest class of people; the rabble. Cf. Rag, tag, and bobtail, under Bobtail. If the tag-rag people did not clap him and hiss him, I am no true man. Shak.
Imposition; fraud. [Colloq.]
That which takes up or tightens; specifically, a device in a sewing machine for drawing up the slack thread as the needle rises, in completing a stitch.
A kind of drum used in the East Indies and other Oriental countries; -- called also tom-tom.
A gong. See Gong, n., 1.
A combining form (also used adjectively) used in chemistry to denote the presence of tartar or of some of its compounds or derivatives.
A combining form from Gr. qe`rmh heat, qermo`s hot, warm; as in thermochemistry, thermodynamic.
A female cat. [Prov. Eng.] Halliwell.
A rod used as a tie. See Tie.
Same as Tip-up.
A combining form (also used adjectively) designating certain double compounds of titanium with some other elements; as, titano- cyanide, titano-fluoride, titano-silicate, etc.
A lean-to. See Lean-to.
See Tam-tam.
A name added, for the sake of distinction, to one's surname, or used instead of it. [Scot.] Jamieson.
A dish made in the West Indies by beating boiled plantain quite soft in a wooden mortar.
Words imitative of the notes of the owl. Thy tu-whits are lulled, I wot, Thy tu-whoos of yesternight. Tennyson.
A line or track leading from the provinces toward the metropolis or a principal terminus; the track upon which up-trains run. See Up-train. [Eng.]

A combining form (also used adjectively) indicating derivation from, or relation to, valerian or some of its products, as valeric acid; as in valerolactone, a colorless oily liquid produced as the anhydride of an hydroxy valeric acid.

A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the abdomen; also, connection with, relation to, or direction toward, the ventral side; as, ventrolateral; ventro- inguinal.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the bla; as in vesicoprostatic, vesicovaginal.

A violent and peremptory procedure without any assigned reason; a sudden conclusive happening. [Obs.] When the church Was taken with a why-not in the lurch. Hudibras. This game . . . was like to have been lost with a why-not. Nugæ Antiq.
Act of winding up, or closing; a concluding act or part; the end.
The agile, or silvery, gibbon; -- called also camper. See Gibbon. [Written also wow-wow.]
See Wou-wou.
A combining form from Gr. xanqo`s yellow; as in xanthocobaltic salts. Used also adjectively in chemistry.
Ambs-ace. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Double aces, the lowest throw of all at dice. Hence: Bad luck; anything of no account or value.
Same as Ambs-ace.
An edentate animal of tropical America (the Tamanoir), living on ants. It belongs to the genus Myrmecophaga.
A mound thrown up by ants or by termites in forming their nests.
A neuropterous insect, the larva of which makes in the sand a pitfall to capture ants, etc. The common American species is Myrmeleon obsoletus, the European is M. formicarius.
A low fire used in chemical operations.
A blowing off steam, water, etc.; -- Also, adj.
as, a blow-off cock or pipe.
An outburst of temper or excitement. [Colloq.]
The cleaning of the flues of a boiler from scale, etc., by a blast of steam.
The blue-cheeked honeysucker of Australia.
A hollow smoothing iron containing a heater within.
Disruption; a separation and dispersion of the parts or members; as, a break-up of an assembly or dinner party; a break-up of the government.
A retired or private place.
A proverb. [Obs.]
The space between two principals or girders.
One of the joists framed between a pair of girders in naked flooring.
One of two small holes astern, above the gunroom ports, through which hawsers may be passed.
A sort of salt, finely granulated, formed out of the bittern or leach brine.

A tall rush or flag (Typha latifolia) growing in marshes, with long, glat leaves, and having its flowers in a close cylindrical spike at the top of the stem. The leaves are frequently used for seating chairs, making mats, etc. See Catkin.
A combining form meaning a grain, granular, granular cartilage, cartilaginous; as, the chondrocranium, the cartilaginous skull of the lower vertebrates and of embryos.
The chick-pea. Holland.
The red, or corn, poppy. [Written also cup-rose.]
Same as prefix Counter-. [Obs.]
A person or animal whose ears are cropped.
A kind of oak-leaf gall. See Gall.
A kind of lichen, of the genus Cladonia.
Red poppy. See Cop-rose.
The upper stratum of coal, as nearest the light or surface.
The dawn. [Poetic] Milton.
The morning star; the star which ushers in the day. A dark place, until the day dawn, and the day-star arise in your hearts. 2 Peter i. 19.

The sun, as the orb of day. [Poetic] So sinks the day-star in the ocean bed, And yet anon repairs his drooping head, And tricks his beams, and with new-spangled ore Flames in the forehead of the morning sky. Milton.

A round, flattish, wooden block, encircled by a rope, or an iron band, and pierced with three holes to receive the lanyard; -- used to extend the shrouds and stays, and for other purposes. Called also deadman's eye. Totten.
Pay drawn for soldiers, or others, really dead, whose names are kept on the rolls. O you commanders, That, like me, have no dead-pays. Massinger.
A common European wild rose, with single pink or white flowers.
A sofa, open carriage, or the like, so constructed that the occupants sit back to back.
A single cut with a knife.
A species of tern, esp. the sooty tern (Sterna fuliginosa) of the West Indies. In the Bahama Islands the name is applied to the tropic bird, Phaëthon flavirostris.
A prefix or combining form signifying pertaining to electricity, produced by electricity, producing or employing electricity, etc.; as, electro-negative; electro-dynamic; electro- magnet.
See Ferro-.
A set of fire irons, including, commonly, tongs, shovel, and poker.
A sudden burst of anger or passion; an angry dispute. [Colloq.]
A kind of low-crowned cap formerly worn by all classes in England, and continued in London after disuse elsewhere; -- hence, a citizen of London. Marston.
The covering of an insect, esp. the elytra of beetles.
A conspiracy or plot, esp. for a malicious or evil purpose, as to incriminate a person on false evidence. [Slang]
See Gaudy, a feast.
A weight which is dropped into a bore, as of an oil well, to explode a cartridge previously lowered.
A device, as a loosely fitted plug, which is driven through a pipe by the pressure of the contents behind the plug to clear away obstructions.
A rough sled or dray used for dragging logs, hauling stone, etc. [Local, U. S.]
A combining form denoting relation to the throat; as, gutturo- nasal, having both a guttural and a nasal character; gutturo-palatal.
See Hæma-.
A straight line considered as drawn from a center to an indefinite distance in one direction, the complete ray being the whole line drawn to an indefinite distance in both directions.
A foolish; a dolt; a blockhead; a dunce. Dryden.
A witch; a hag. Middleton.
The European green woodpecker or yaffle. [Written also high- hoo.]
A laced boot, ankle high.
A ship's masthead. Shak.
A violent, passionate person; a hasty or impetuous person; as, the rant of a hot-head.

A combining form, also used adjectively, indicating hydroxyl as an ingredient. Hydroxy acid (Chem.), an organic acid, having (besides the hydroxyl group of the carboxyl radical) an alcoholic hydroxyl group, and thus having the qualities of an alcohol in addition to its acid properties; as, lactic and tartaric acids are hydroxy acids.
. See under Ill, a.
A pole for supporting a scaffold.
The act of going in; entrance.
Depression of the jaw; hence, depression of spirits. M. Griffith (1660).
A machine for bending or straightening rails.
A planing machine with a reversing tool, to plane both ways.
One who causes gloom or grief; a dispiriting person. W. Black.
One who knows everything; hence, one who makes pretension to great knowledge; a wiseacre; -- usually ironical. [Colloq. or R.]
A thin, flat piece of board in the form of a quadrant of a circle attached to the log line; -- called also log-ship. See 2d Log, n., 2.
A part of the log. See Log-chip, and 2d Log, n., 2.
The state attending, and consequent to, childbirth; confinement.
The act of bearing a child.
A prefix meaning pertaining to, produced by, or in some way connected with, magnetism.
A blundering preacher.
The marigold; a blossom of the marigold. Shak.
A eye affected by the moon; also, a disease in the eye of a horse.
Any species of American fresh-water fishes of the genus Hyodon, esp. H. tergisus of the Great Lakes and adjacent waters.
The cisco.
(. (Chem.) A prefix (also used adjectively) designating the group or radical NO, called the nitroso group, or its compounds.
A combining form indicating connection with, or relation to, the umbilicus, or navel.
A combining form fr. Gr.
A combining form used to indicate connection with, or relation to, the parietal bones or the parietal segment of the skull; as, the parieto-mastoid suture.
A key for opening more locks than one; a master key.
A combining form, denoting relation to, or dependence upon, natural causes, or the science of physics.
A pit; a pockmark.
A prefix. See Preter-.
Any one of numerous species of beautiful humming birds of the genus Eriocnemis having large tufts of downy feathers on the legs.
A punt made from the goal line by a player of the side which has made a touchdown to one of his own side for a fair catch, from which an attempt to kick a goal may be made.
The American night heron. See under Night.
A combining form meaning five, five times, fivefold; as, quinquefid, five-cleft; quinquedentate, five-toothed.
An excrescence growing from the pastern to the middle of the shank of a horse.
The California chimæra. See Chimæra.
Any fish of the genus Macrurus. See Grenadier, 2.
See Veda.
The act of collecting or gathering together scattered cattle by riding around them and driving them in. [Western U.S.]
The sound of a drum when continuously beaten; hence, a clamorous, repeated sound; a clatter. The rubadub of the abolition presses. D. Webster.
Anything which saves fragments, or prevents waste or loss. Specifically:
A device in a candlestick to hold the ends of candles, so that they be burned.
A small North American owl (Nyctale Acadica), destitute of ear tufts and having feathered toes; -- called also Acadian owl.
Any plant of the composite genus Serratula; -- so named from the serrated leaves of most of the species.
A powerful instrument of brass, curved somewhat like the Roman buccina, or tuba.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the scapula or the shoulder; as, the scapulo- clavicular articulation, the articulation between the scapula and clavicle.
A long, rolling swell of the sea. Ham. Nav. Encyc.
The mermaid.
A sea nymph.
A gull; the mew.
The sea mew.
A species of lac. See the Note under Lac.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting the presence of selenium or its compounds; as, selenio-phosphate, a phosphate having selenium in place of all, or a part, of the oxygen.
In plastering, a particularly good troweled surface. Knight.
The game of cards called also all fours, and old sledge. [U. S.]
The unkempt and ragged part of the community. [Colloq. or Slang.] R. Browning.
, adv. & a. Very high. [Colloq.]
One who, or that which, stands by one in need; something upon which one relies for constant use or in an emergency.
One who comes suddenly into notice; an upstart. [Obs.] Shak.
A kind of high rustic shoe. [Obs.] Drayton. A startuppe, or clownish shoe. Spenser.
That which closes or fills up an opening or gap; hence, a temporary expedient. Moral prejudices are the stop-gaps of virtue. Hare.
The lowest member of a base when divided horizontally, or of a baseboard, pedestal, or the like.
The deepest pedal stop, or the lowest tones of an organ; the fundamental or ground bass. [Written also sub-base.] Ayliffe.
One of the joists which rest one end on the wall and the other on a girder; also, the space between a wall and the nearest girder of a floor. Cf. Case-bay.
The part of a canal lock below the lower gates.
An imitation, especially in the way of caricature.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the temple, or temporal bone; as, temporofacial.
A rope used for hoisting and lowering a topmast, and for other purposes.
A tool applied to the top of the work, in distinction from a tool inserted in the anvil and on which the work is placed.
An urchin who has soft, whitish hair. [Colloq.]
The hooded merganser. [ Local, U.S. ]
See Tuck, n., 2.
See Tuyère.
A tunnel. [Obs.] Shak.
The act of coming forth; a leaving of houses, shops, etc.; esp., a quitting of employment for the purpose of forcing increase of wages; a strike; -- opposed to lockout.
A short side track on a railroad, which may be occupied by one train while another is passing on a main track; a shunt; a siding; a switch.
That which is prominently brought forward or exhibited; hence, an equipage; as, a man with a showy carriage and horses is said to have a fine turn-out.
The aggregate number of persons who have come out, as from their houses, for a special purpose.
Net quantity of produce yielded.
A snub nose. [Prov. Eng.]
Work done by the piece, as in nonmetaliferous rock, the amount done being usually reckoned by the fathom. Tomlinson.
A kind of round dance in march or polka time; also, a piece of music for this dance. [U. S.]
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the tympanum; as in tympanohyal, tympano-Eustachian.
A train going in the direction of the metropolis or the main terminus. [Eng.]
A train going in the direction conventionally called up. [U.S.]
The bearberry.
See Otaheite apple.
An eye in which the iris is of a very light gray or whitish color; -- said usually of horses. Booth.
An American fresh-water food fish (Stizostedion vitreum) having large and prominent eyes; -- called also glasseye, pike perch, yellow pike, and wall-eyed perch.
A California surf fish (Holconotus argenteus).
The alewife; -- called also wall-eyed herring.

The end of the week; specif., though loosely, the period observed commonly as a holiday, from Saturday noon or Friday night to Monday; as, to visit one for a week-end; also, a house party during a week-end.
' (as, a would-be poet.
A species of elm (Ulmus montana) found in Northern and Western Europe; Scotch elm.
A low, shrubby, rubiaceous plant (Morinda Royoc) growing along the seacoast of the West Indies. It has small, white, odorous flowers.

An edentate mammal, of the genus Orycteropus, somewhat resembling a pig, common in some parts of Southern Africa. It burrows in the ground, and feeds entirely on ants, which it catches with its long, slimy tongue.
A carnivorous quadruped (Proteles Lalandii), of South Africa, resembling the fox and hyena. See Proteles.
Wisdom or perception that comes after it can be of use. "After- wit comes too late when the mischief is done." L'Estrange.
Same as Agar-agar.
A fucus or seaweed much used in the East for soups and jellies; Ceylon moss (Gracilaria lichenoides).
The adjutant of a regiment.
A stove the draft of which can be almost entirely shut off. [Colloq. U. S.]
One of several species of edentates and monotremes that feed upon ants. See Ant-bear, Pangolin, Aard-vark, and Echidna.
A kind of broadax formerly used as an offensive weapon.
A bird of the genus Merops, that feeds on bees. The European species (M. apiaster) is remarkable for its brilliant colors.
An African bird of the genus Rhinopomastes.
One whose great pleasure it is to gratify his appetite; a glutton; an epicure.
A name given to fluor spar in Derbyshire, where it is used for ornamental purposes.
A large grackle or blackbird (Quiscalus major), found in the Southern United States.
The bells of Bow Church in London; cockneydom. People born within the sound of Bow-bells are usually called cockneys. Murray's Handbook of London.
A kind of fox found in Sweden (Vulpes alopex), smaller than the common fox (V. vulgaris), but probably a variety of it.
A rustic wedding feast; a bridal. See Ale. The man that 's bid to bride-ale, if he ha' cake, And drink enough, he need not fear his stake. B. Jonson.
The common European starfish (Asterias rubens).
One who bids at an auction in behalf of the auctioneer or owner, for the purpose of running up the price of articles. [U.S.]
A private corner. Britain being a by-corner, out of the road of the world. Fuller.
An incidental or casual speech, not directly relating to the point. "To quote by-speeches." Hooker.
A separate, private, or obscure street; an out of the way or cross street. He seeks by-streets, and saves the expensive coach. Gay.
An accidental or a slyly given stroke.
Same as Calcite.
See under Calcite.
A variety of quartz or chalcedony, exhibiting opalescent reflections from within, like the eye of a cat. The mane is given to other gems affording like effects, esp. the chrysoberyl.
A light transitory air which ruffles the surface of the water during a calm, or the ripples made by such a puff of air.
A particular hitch or turn in the bight of a rope, into which a tackle may be hooked.
A dupe; a tool; one who, or that which, is used by another as an instrument to a accomplish his purposes.
A Small leguminous plant (Cicer arietinum) of Asia, Africa, and the sounth of Europe; the chick; the dwarf pea; the gram.
Its nutritious seed, used in cookery, and especially, when roasted (parched pulse), as food for travelers in the Eastern deserts.
A feast for the benefit of the parish clerk. [Eng.] T. Warton.
A rushlike plant, the reed mace or cat-tail, or some species of the genus Scirpus. See Bulrush.
A partner in a lease taen.
A partner in giving a lease.

A large hemipterous insect of the family Reduviidæ, often found in houses, esp. in the southern and western United States. It bites severely, and is one of the species called kissing bugs. It is also called big bedbug.
Same as Corallian.
A joint regent or ruler.
A handsomely banded, coral-reef fish, of Florida and the West Indies (Pomacentrus saxatilis); -- called also mojarra.
A disease in the West Indies. It is a kind of ulcer on the soles of the feet, with very hard edges. See Yaws. Dunglison.
A kind of gambling game consisting in pitching coins to or towards the ceiling of a room so that they shall fall as near as possible to a certain crack in the floor. [Gamblers' Cant, U. S.]
A bun or cake marked with a cross, and intended to be eaten on Good Friday.
See Strabismus.
A sleeper supporting and connecting the rails, and holding them in place.
A saw in the form of a hollow cylinder, with teeth on the end or edge, and operated by a rotative motion.
A filamentous fresh-water alga (Conferva rivularis of Linnaeus, Rhizoclonium rivulare of Kutzing).
Labor hired or performed by the day. Milton.

A person who is deaf and dumb; one who, through deprivation or defect of hearing, has either failed the acquire the power of speech, or has lost it. [See Illust. of Dactylology.] Deaf-mutes are still so called, even when, by artificial methods, they have been taught to speak imperfectly.
A man employed in decoying wild fowl.
A deerlike, or thin, ill-formed neck, as of a horse.
The temperature at which dew begins to form. It varies with the humidity and temperature of the atmosphere.
One who often takes his dinner away from home, or in company. A brilliant diner-out, though but a curate. Byron.
A sailor's small bag to hold thread, needles, tape, etc.; -- also called sailor's housewife.
A small box to hold a sailor's thread, needless, comb, etc.
A small tree of tropical America (Cæsalpinia coriaria), whose legumes contain a large proportion of tannic and gallic acid, and are used by tanners and dyers.
The dog-rose.
The corner of a leaf, in a book, turned down like the ear of a dog. Gray.  -- Dog's"-eared`, a. Cowper.
One who performs little though professing much. [Colloq.] Great talkers are commonly dolittles. Bp. Richardson.
A lazy, good-for-nothing fellow.
A chart of previous performances, etc., of race horses. [Race- track Slang]
A weight, consisting of two spheres or spheroids, connected by a short bar for a handle; used (often in pairs) for gymnastic exercise.
A flattened marine univalve shell of the genus Haliotis; -- called also sea-ear. See Abalone.
A small sandglass, running about three minutes, for marking time in boiling eggs; also, a small glass for holding an egg, at table.
A going out of the way; a digression. [Obs.] Fuller.

A system of spirit influences for good and evil believed by the Chinese to attend the natural features of landscape; also, a kind of geomancy dealing with these influences, used in determining sites for graves, houses, etc.
A time of feasting or celebration; an anniversary day of joy, civil or religious. The morning trumpets festival proclaimed. Milton.
A marine univalve shell of the genus Pyrula, or Ficula, resembling a fig in form.
Cinquefoil; five-finger.
The bite of a flea, or the red spot caused by the bite.
A trifling wound or pain, like that of the bite of a flea. Harvey.
The repeated stroke of something long and loose. Johnson.
A species of tenure in fee simple, being the opposite of ancient demesne, or copyhold. Burrill.

The liberty of being sworn in courts, as a juror or witness; one of the ancient privileges of a freeman; free and common law; -- an obsolete expression signifying substantially the same as the American expression civil rights. Abbot.
The doctrine or practice of consorting with the opposite sex, at pleasure, without marriage.
Frogbit.
An organ stop with conical tin pipes.
Something which gets or gains money; a successful affair. [Colloq.] Chapman.
The venereal disease; -- often used as a mild oath. [Obs.] Shak.
A prominent belly; a big-bellied person. [Obs.]
The great woolly mullein (Verbascum Thapsus).
A variety of native Epsom salt occurring in silky fibers.
A boot with a short top covering only the ankle. See Cocker, and Congress boot, under Congress.
A shell of the genus Crepidula; a boat shell. See Boat shell.
See Half deck, under Deck.
A salmon in its fifth year of growth. [Prov. Eng.]
A point some distance below the top of a mast or staff; as, a flag a half-mast (a token of mourning, etc.).
The moon at the quarters, when half its disk appears illuminated.
The shape of a half-moon; a crescent. See how in warlike muster they appear, In rhombs, and wedges, and half-moons, and wings. Milton.
An outwork composed of two faces, forming a salient angle whose gorge resembles a half-moon; -- now called a ravelin.
A marine, sparoid, food fish of California (Cæsiosoma Californiense). The body is ovate, blackish above, blue or gray below. Called also medialuna.
A short pike, sometimes carried by officers of infantry, sometimes used in boarding ships; a spontoon. Tatler.
One half of a shutter made in two parts for closing a porthole.

The official stamp of the Goldsmiths' Company and other assay offices, in the United Kingdom, on gold and silver articles, attesting their purity. Also used figuratively; -- as, a word or phrase lacks the hall-mark of the best writers.
A small hole in a boiler for the insertion of the hand in cleaning, etc. Hand-hole plate, the cover of a hand-hole.
One who hangs on, or sticks to, a person, place, or service; a dependent; one who adheres to others' society longer than he is wanted. Goldsmith.

Suicide, by slashing the abdomen, formerly practiced in Japan, and commanded by the government in the cases of disgraced officials; disembowelment; -- also written, but incorrectly, hari-kari. W. E. Griffis.
A name given by soldiers and sailors to a kind of hard biscuit or sea bread.
A superior officer or official; -- used chiefly in pl. [Slang]
A plant of the genus Verbascum (V. Thapsus); the common mullein. [Also high-taper and hag-taper.]
The receptacle for honey in a honeybee. Shak. Grew.
See Hop-o'-my-thumb.
A tune played on the horn very early in the morning to call out the hunters; hence, any arousing sound or call. [Obs.] Shak. Time plays the hunt's-up to thy sleepy head. Drayton.
An old game played with four dice. In signified a doublet, or two dice alike; in-and-in, either two doubles, or the four dice alike.
A species of fungus (Hirneola Auricula-Judæ, or Auricula), bearing some resemblance to the human ear.
A genus (Ephedra) of leafless shrubs, with the stems conspicuously jointed; -- called also shrubby horsetail. There are about thirty species, of which two or three are found from Texas to California.
See Kiefekil.

A member of a common form of truss, as a roof truss. It is strictly a tie, intended to prevent the sagging of the tiebeam in the middle. If there are struts, supporting the main rafters, they often bear upon the foot of the king-post. Called also crown-post.
Act or place of knocking off; that which knocks off; specif. (Mach.),
a cam or the like for disconnecting something, as a device in a knitting machine to remove loops from the needles.
Act of knocking out, or state of being knocked out.
A variety of cabbage, in which the edible part is a large, turnip-shaped swelling of the stem, above the surface of the ground.
See Japan Current, above.
A shrub in the West Indies (Lagetta Iintearia); -- so called from the lacelike layers of its inner bark.
A post (generally a pillar of iron) supporting a lamp or lantern for lighting a street, park, etc.
The European meadow pipit; -- called also titling.
A contrivance to fasten logs together in rafting; -- used by lumbermen. [U.S.]
A waste weir for a canal, discharging into a lock chamber.
An old name for a pilot boat.
One who is set to stop balls which pass the wicket keeper.
A gentle gale of wind.
The Pomeranian or Spitz dog.
Actinomycosis. [Colloq.]
See Eggplant.
A magpie. [Obs.] Shak.
An object of ridicule; a butt. Godwin.
The act of bringing spirits to a certain degree of strength, called proof.
The act of becoming reconciled or friendly.
See Malodor.

One who, or that which, has an appetite for human flesh; specifically, one of certain large sharks (esp. Carcharodon Rondeleti); also, a lion or a tiger which has acquired the habit of feeding upon human flesh.
Lady; mistress; -- used by Hindustani-speaking natives in India in addressing European women.
The incorporated materials for gunpowder, in the form of a dense mass or cake, ready to be subjected to the process of granulation.
An apparatus for raising a liquid by pressure of air or steam in a reservoir containing the liquid.
A hall for public meetings; a hall of judgment. [Obs.] "The moot-hall of Herod." Wyclif.
A hill of meeting or council; an elevated place in the open air where public assemblies or courts were held by the Saxons; -- called, in Scotland, mute-hill. J. R. Green.
The forget-me-not (Myosotis palustris) and other species of the same genus.

A European species of hawkweed (Hieracium Pilosella). Mouse-ear chickweed, a name of two common species of chickweed (Cerastium vulgarium, and C. viscosum).  -- Mouse-ear cress, a low cruciferous herb (Sisymbrium Thaliana). All these are low herbs with soft, oval, or obovate leaves, whence the name.
See Moot-hill. [Scot.]

A member of a body of French painters (F. les néo-Grecs) of the middle 19th century. The term is rather one applied by outsiders to certain artists of grave and refined style, such as Hamon and Aubert, than a name adopted by the artists themselves.
A newspaper. [Obs.]
A white-flowered rosaceous shrub (Neillia, or Spiræa, opulifolia), common in the Northern United States. The bark separates into many thin layers, whence the name.
The lamprey.
A combining form denoting relation to, or situation near, the occiput; as, occipito-axial; occipito-mastoid.
A hanger-on.
A looker-on.
The small, blueblack, drupelike fruit of the Nuttallia cerasiformis, a shrub of Oregon and California, belonging to the Cherry tribe of Rosaceæ.

A game formerly common in England, in which a wooden ball was driven with a mallet through an elevated hoop or ring of iron. The name was also given to the mallet used, to the place where the game was played, and to the street, in London, still called Pall Mall. [Written also pail-mail and pell-mell.] Sir K. Digby. Evelyn.
One who goes by; a passer.
See Pall-mall.
Eyeglasses kept on the nose by a spring.
An indoor modification of lawn tennis played with small bats, or battledores, and a very light, hollow, celluloid ball, on a large table divided across the middle by a net.
A size of photograph a little larger than a postage stamp.
Pitchblende.
A combining form from Gr. wind, air, breath, respiration; as, pneumatograph, pneumatology.
A small European fish, similar to the cod, but of inferior quality. Poor-john and apple pies are all our fare. Sir J. Harrington.
A bird of the Western United States (Phalænoptilus Nutalli) allied to the whip-poor-will.
A duty paid to the king by the cognizee in a fine of lands, when the same was fully passed; -- called also the king's silver.

A bond in which the obligor, in consideration of having received a certain sum of money, binds himself to pay a larger sum, on unusual interest, on the death of some specified individual from whom he has expectations. Bouvier.

A bond in which the obligor, in consideration of having received a certain sum of money, binds himself to pay a larger sum, on unusual interest, on the death of some specified individual from whom he has expectations.  Bouvier.
A protuberant belly.
A hoe with prongs to break the earth.

A combining form signifying of a purple or purple-red color. Specif. (Chem.), used in designating certain brilliant purple-red compounds of cobaltic chloride and ammonia, similar to the roseocobaltic compounds. See Cobaltic.
An instigator. Shak.
A rent of the full annual value of the tenement, or near it; an excessive or unreasonably high rent. Blackstone.
See Rake, a mineral vein.
The cat-tail.
A piece of canvas sewed across a sail to strengthen it in the part where the eyelet holes for reefing are made. Totten.
Rolly-poly.
the yarn or thread of any stuff of which the strands of a rope are made.
A name of several English gold coins struck in different reigns and having having different values; a rose noble.
A kind of turnip commonly with a large and long or ovoid yellowish root; a Swedish turnip. See Turnip.
See Saw-set.
A blue-flowered labiate plant (Brunella vulgaris); the healall.
The act of aiding one's self, without depending on the aid of others.
Life for one's self; living solely or chiefly for one's own pleasure or good.
The love of one's self; desire of personal happiness; tendency to seek one's own benefit or advantage. Shak. Self-love, the spring of motion, acts the soul. Pope.
A view if one's self; specifically, carefulness or regard for one's own interests
One's own will, esp. when opposed to that of others; obstinacy.
A person tolerated only because he pays the shot, or reckoning, for the rest of the company, otherwise a mere clog on them. [Old Slang] Thou common shot-clog, gull of all companies. Chapman.
See Schwan-pan.
The kob.
One who sneaks from his cups; one who balks his glass. [Obs.] Shak.
A tart dialogue with quick replies. [R.] Pope.
Combining forms from Gr. seed, sperm, semen (of plants or animals); as, spermatoblast, spermoblast.
A kind of palsy affecting the jaw of a horse. Crabb.
Doctrine or knowledge of the stars; star lore; astrology; astronomy. [Obs.] Which in star-read were wont have best insight. Spenser.
See the Note under Lac.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting a sulphate as an ingredient in certain double salts; as, sulphato-carbonate. [R.]
A bow-saw.
A kind of custard apple (Anona squamosa). See under Custard.
A variety of the chicken pox, with acuminated vesicles containing a watery fluid; the water pox. Pepys.
A Central American name for the ivory nut.
A book with wide spaces between the lines, to give room for notes.
A volume, as of some classical author, on which a teacher lectures or comments; hence, any manual of instruction; a schoolbook.
A large hand in writing; -- so called because it was the practice to write the text of a book in a large hand and the notes in a smaller hand.
A start in a hunt or a race. [Eng.]
A siliceous stone of a yellow color and chatoyant luster, obtained in South Africa and much used for ornament. It is an altered form of the mineral crocidolite. See Crocidolite.
A mill where a tilt hammer is used, or where the process of tilting is carried on.
A yard or place for tilting. "The tilt-yard of Templestowe." Sir W. Scott.
The part of a toolrest in which a cutting tool is clamped.
the part that supports a tool-post or a tool.
A top railing supported by stanchions and equipped with netting.
A large ironbound block strapped with a hook, and, when used, hung to an eyebolt in the cap, -- used in swaying and lowering the topmast. Totten.
High boots, having generally a band of some kind of light- colored leather around the upper part of the leg; riding boots.
A chain for slinging the lower yards, in time of action, to prevent their falling, if the ropes by which they are hung are shot away.
A piece of canvas used to cover the hammocks which are lashed to the top in action to protect the topmen.
A lantern or light on the top of a vessel.
Any one of numerous species of marine top_shaped shells of the genus Thochus, or family Trochidæ.
A box containing lighted tinder, formerly carried by soldiers who used matchlocks, to kindle the match.
An old game played with dice. [Obs.] Shak.
The third tine above the base of a stag's antler; the royal antler.

In the antler of a stag, the third tyne above the base. This tyne appears in the third year. In those deer in which the brow tyne does not divide, the tres-tyne is the second tyne above the base. See Illust. under Rucervine, and under Rusine.
A person of inflexible integrity or fidelity.
A pair of blacksmith's tongs.

A burrowing South American rodent (Ctenomys Braziliensis). It has small eyes and ears and a short tail. It resembles the pocket gopher in size, form, and habits, but is more nearly allied to the porcupines. [Written also tucu-tuco.]
A disease with which sheep are sometimes affected; gid; sturdy. See Gid.
A two-stroke cycle for an internal-combustion engine. --Two"- cy`cle, a.
The orang-utang
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, a vertebra, vertebræ, or vertebral column; as in vertebrocostal.
One who, or that which, is face to face with another; esp., one who faces another in dancing.
A carriage in which two persons sit face to face. Also, a form of sofa with seats for two persons, so arranged that the occupants are face to face while sitting on opposite sides.
A fulling mill. [Prov. Eng.] Halliwell.
In racing, the going over a course by a horse which has no competitor for the prize; hence, colloquially, a one-sided contest; an uncontested, or an easy, victory.
The spotted flycatcher. It builds its nest on walls. [Prov. Eng.]
The duty of keeping watch and ward (see the Note under Watch, n., 1) with a horn to be blown upon any occasion of surprise. Burrill.
See Wayz-goose, n., 2. [Eng.]
The wych-elm. [Obs.] Bacon.
The wryneck; -- so called from its cry. [Prov. Eng.]
The common European sandpiper.
The chaffinch. [Prov. Eng.]
A wish of happiness. "A well-wish for his friends." Addison.
The wheatear.

Any one of several species of small Old World singing of the genus Zosterops, as Zosterops palpebrosus of India, and Z. coerulescens of Australia. The eyes are encircled by a ring of white feathers, whence the name. Called also bush creeper, and white-eyed tit.
A kind of food made of milk or cream, eggs, sugar, bread, etc., baked in a pot. King.
A disease in the feet of a horse or other beast.
Any weak, thin drink.
See Wych-elm.
A North American shrub (Viburnum nudum) whose tough osierlike shoots are sometimes used for binding sheaves.
A wild or natural note, as of a forest bird. [R.] Or sweetest Shakespeare, fancy's child, Warble his native wood-notes wild. Milton.
A kind of froth seen on herbs. [Obs.]
The time when there no sap in the trees; the winter season. [Written also wood-seer.] [Obs.] Tusser.
Same as Woadwaxen.
A trade market in the woolen districts. [Eng.]
An A-B-C book; a primer. [Obs.] Shak.
A glow of refulgence in the western sky after sunset.
One of the small notes occur on the unaccented parts of the measure, taking their time from the preceding note.
A pot companion. [Obs.]
Various kinds of plant lice or aphids tended by ants for the sake of the honeydew which they secrete. See Aphips.
An antimask. B. Jonson.
A tropical wind blowing steadily in a direction opposite to the trade wind.
Apple brandy. [U.S.]
A kind of apple which by keeping becomes much withered; -- called also Johnapple. Shak.
A judgment of the Inquisition in Spain and Portugal condemning or acquitting persons accused of religious offenses.
An execution of such sentence, by the civil power, esp. the burning of a heretic. It was usually held on Sunday, and was made a great public solemnity by impressive forms and ceremonies.
A session of the court of Inquisition.
Same as Auto-da-fé.
A vessel for holding hot water in which another vessel may be heated without scorching its contents; -- used for warming or preparing food or pharmaceutical preparations.
The secondary, inferior, or rear courtyard of a large house; the outer court of a castle.
An inferior court of law, not of record.
Low relief; sculpture, the figures of which project less than half of their true proportions; -- called also bassrelief and basso- rilievo. See Alto-rilievo.
The second tine of a stag's horn. See under Antler.
A kind of primrose (Primula auricula), so called from the shape of the leaf.
A large bivalve shell of the East Indies (Hippopus maculatus), often used as an ornament.
A fine genius, or man of wit. "A man of letters and a bel esprit." W. Irving.
Same as Bez-antler.
The second branch of a stag's horn.
A plant with a small bright flower, as the Adonis or pheasant's eye, the mealy primrose (Primula farinosa), and species of Veronica, Geranium, etc.
A name given by English miners to sphalerite, or zinc blende; - - called also false galena. See Blende.
Caramel or burnt sugar, used to color wines, spirits, ground coffee, etc.
A large leather vessel for beer, etc. [Obs.]
The Quercus nigra, or barren oak.
The ensign of a pirate.
A play among children, in which a cherry, hung so as to bob against the mouth, is to be caught with the teeth.
Good will; good fellowship; agreement. [Scot.]
A factotum. [R.] He is his master's both-hands, I assure you. B. Jonson.
Bow-compasses, one leg of which carries a pencil.
A small circular or oval wooden block without sheaves, having a groove around it and a hole through it, used for connecting rigging.
A small round cloud, with a ruddy center, supposed by sailors to portend a storm.
A small thick disk of glass inserted in a deck, roof, floor, ship's side, etc., to let in light.
A circular or oval opening for air or light.
A lantern, with a thick glass lens on one side for concentrating the light on any object; also, the lens itself. Dickens.
Aldebaran, a bright star in the eye of Taurus or the Bull.
The center of a target.
A thick knob or protuberance left on glass by the end of the pipe through which it was blown.
A small and thick old-fashioned watch. [Colloq.]
A passage different from the usual one; a byway.
A secondary or additional product; something produced, as in the course of a manufacture, in addition to the principal product.
Private end or view; by-interest. [Obs.] Dryden.
An obscure road; a way turning from the main road. Sir P. Sidney.
A small war club, esp. of savages; -- so called because of its supposed use in crushing the skull.
See Cat-harping.
A plant (Nepeta Glechoma) of the same genus with catnip; ground ivy.
Mica. [Archaic]
See Timothy, Cat-tail, Cirrus.
A seller of low-priced or second goods; a hawker.
One who bandies words or is very argunentative. [Jocular] Shak.
A church or parish festival (as in commemoration of the dedication of a church), at which much ale was used. Wright. Nares.
Churchyard. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A licensed or official coal measurer in London. See Meter. Simmonds.
See Lumpfish. [Scot.]
A joint legatee.
A gripping device, as for stretching wire, etc., consisting of two jaws so attached to a ring that they are closed by pulling on the ring.
One who comes out or withdraws from a religious or other organization; a radical reformer. [Colloq. U. S.]
A court of record held once a year, in a particular hundred, lordship, or manor, before the steward of the leet. Blackstone.
A mill for grinding tin ore.
The three days preceding the Feast of the Ascension.
Same as Cross-spale.
A bar connecting the ends of the side rods or levers of a backaction or side-lever engine.
Rogation week, when the cross was borne in processions.
Same as King-post.
A quill of the crow, or a very fine pen made from such a quill.
A passage with only one outlet, as a street closed at one end; a blind alley; hence, a trap.
a position in which an army finds itself with no way of exit but to the front.
Any bag-shaped or tubular cavity, vessel, or organ, open only at one end.
A bantam fowl.
A reckless fellow. Also used adjectively; as, dare-devil excitement. A humorous dare-devil -- the very man To suit my prpose. Ld. Lytton.
A duck used to lure wild ducks into a decoy; hence, a person employed to lure others into danger. Beau. & Fl.
A small cup for, or of, black coffee.
Nipplewort.
See Dogbane.
A breastplow used in paring off turf on downs. [Eng.] Knight.
An old rural game. With any boy at dust-point they shall play. Peacham (1620).
An armichair for ease or repose. "Laugh . . . in Rabelais' easy-chair." Pope.
The eelpout.
State of prosperity. [Obs.] They think it was never fair-world with them since. Milton.
One who deliberately puts an end to his own existence, or loses his life while engaged in the commission of an unlawful or malicious act; a suicide. Burrill.

A pheasantlike bird of rich plumage and graceful form and movement, fabled to appear in the land on the accession of a sage to the throne, or when right principles are about to prevail. It is often represented on porcelains and other works of art.
The spur-winged goose; -- so called from the red circle around the eyes.
A war vessel of the highest grade or the most powerful class.
See Fish-tackle.

A plant in new Zealand (Phormium tenax), allied to the lilies and aloes. The leaves are two inches wide and several feet long, and furnish a fiber which is used for making ropes, mats, and coarse cloth.
A jumping plant louse of the family Psyllidæ, of many species. That of the pear tree is Psylla pyri.
A woman of light behavior; a gill-flirt. [Obs.] Shak. You heard him take me up like a flirt-gill. Beau. & Fl.
A variety of aragonite, occuring in delicate white coralloidal forms; -- common in beds of iron ore.
A stupid or insignaficant fellow; a fool; a simpleton. [R.] Hudibras.
The evening between twilight and bedtime. [Scot.]
The Tasmanian forty-spotted diamond bird (Pardalotus quadragintus).
A four-stroke cycle, as the Otto cycle, for an internal- combustion engine. -- Four"-cy`cle, a.
One who gratifies his appetites without stint; one given to indulgence in eating and drinking.
One who believes in or practices free-love.
The jet piece of a gas fixture where the gas is burned as it escapes from one or more minute orifices.
A person without thought fulness, prudence, or judgment. [Colloq.] Burton.
A bird referred to in the Bible (Lev. xi. 18and Deut. xiv. 17) as unclean, probably the Egyptian vulture (Neophron percnopterus).
A thoughtless, giddy girl; a flirt-gill. Sir W. Scott.
The larval state (Phyllosoma) of the genus Palinurus and allied genera. It is remarkable for its strange outlines, thinness, and transparency. See Phyllosoma.
A remarkable vitreous sponge, of the genus Hyalonema, first brought from Japan. It has a long stem, consisting of a bundle of long and large, glassy, siliceous fibers, twisted together.
An intermediate agent; a broker; a procurer; -- usually in a disparaging sense. Shak.

One of two or more species of American fresh-water fishes of the family Centrarchidæ, esp. Chænobryttus antistius, of Lake Michigan and adjacent waters, and Ambloplites rupestris, of the Great Lakes and Mississippi Valley; -- so called from their prominent eyes.
The goggler.

A duck (Glaucionetta clangula), found in Northern Europe, Asia, and America. The American variety (var. Americana) is larger. Called whistler, garrot, gowdy, pied widgeon, whiteside, curre, and doucker. Barrow's golden-eye of America (G. Islandica) is less common.

A tall herb (Solidago Virga-aurea), bearing yellow flowers in a graceful elongated cluster. The name is common to all the species of the genus Solidago. Golden-rod tree (Bot.), a shrub (Bosea Yervamora), a native of the Canary Isles.
A galoche.
A glutton. [Low] Todd.
An Australian parrakeet (Polytelis Barrabandi); -- called also the scarlet-breasted parrot.
Having only the back and corners in leather, as a book.
A person who is blooded; the offspring of parents of different races, especially of the American Indian and the white race.
One born of a European parent on the one side, and of a Hindoo or Mohammedan on the other. Also adjective; as, half-caste parents.
An English coin of the value of half a penny; also, the value of half a penny.
Half the length of a sword; close fight. "At half-sword." Shak.
An umbelliferous plant (Bupleurum rotundifolium ); -- so named from the shape of its leaves. Dr. Prior.
An Asiatic species of Cacalia (C. Kleinia), used medicinally in India.
A vessel whose deck consists almost wholly of movable hatches; -- used mostly in the fisheries.
A machine in which hay is chopped short, as fodder for cattle.
The eye or loop formed in each heddle to receive a warp thread.
The dabchick.
An umbelliferous plant (Caucalis daucoides).
A woman that sells herbs.
A hogback.
A hospital.
The kestrel.
One who wishes ill to another; an enemy.

A member of one of the native races of India of Aryan speech and blood, characterized by tall stature, dolichocephaly, fair complexion with dark hair and eyes, plentiful beard, and narrow and prominent nose.

A large, handsome, North American woodpecker (Campephilus principalis), having a large, sharp, ivory-colored beak. Its general color is glossy black, with white secondaries, and a white dorsal stripe. The male has a large, scarlet crest. It is now rare, and found only in the Gulf States.
The shackle for joining a chain cable to an anchor.
A light, giddy, or wanton girl or woman. See Gill-flirt.
A boat of medium size belonging to a ship.
A term applied to many American Mesozoic strata, in which the characteristics of the Jurassic and Triassic periods appear to be blended.  -- Ju`ra-tri*as"sic, a.
The body of servants employed in the kitchen. [Obs.] Holland.
A condition in which the knees are bent in so as to touch each other in walking; inknee.
Having edges or ends united by a lap weld; as, a lap-welded pipe.
Having a leaflike membrane on the nose; -- said of certain bats, esp. of the genera Phyllostoma and Rhinonycteris. See Vampire.
Light-ship.
