A vessel carrying at the masthead a brilliant light, and moored off a shoal or place of dangerous navigation as a guide for mariners.
Aloes wood, or agallochum. See Agallochum.
A fragrant tree mentioned in the Bible. Num. xxiv. 6.
A very brave person.
See Lockjaw.
Long-sightedness Good.
A werewolf; a lycanthrope.
Affection. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A magpie. [Obs.] Shak.
See Maul-stick.
A chiton.
A man who has authority to act, within certain limits, as master of the house; a steward; also, a chief minister or officer.
A peacemaker. [R.] Shak.

A government vessel employed for the purposes of war, esp. one of large size; a ship of war. Man-of-war bird (Zoöl.), The frigate bird; also applied to the skua gulls, and to the wandering albatross.  -- Man-of-war hawk (Zoöl.), the frigate bird.  -- Man-of-war's man, a sailor serving in a ship of war.  -- Portuguese man-of-war (Zoöl.), any species of the genus Physalia. See Physalia.
A warden of the marches; a marcher.
A coat made of match-cloth.
A stick used by painters as a rest for the hand while working. [Written also mahl-stick.]
Of or pertaining to the Middle Ages; mediæval.
Minced meat; meat chopped very fine; a mixture of boiled meat, suet, apples, etc., chopped very fine, to which spices and raisins are added; -- used in making mince pie.
See Mollemoke.
See Nepenthes.

The fruit of two South American trees (Lecythis Ollaria, and L. Zabucajo), which have for their fruit large, pot-shaped, woody capsules containing delicious nuts, and opening almost explosively by a circular lid at the top. Vases and pots are made of this capsule.
An acid elevator, as a tube through which acid is forced to some height in a sulphuric acid manufactory.
See Mule, 4.
A game of hazard played with cards in silence. [Obs. or Prov. Eng.] Decker.
A silent, stupid person. [Prov. Eng.] Halliwell.
An African bird of the genus Schizorhis, related to the plantain eaters.
A taking by surprise; an unexpected onset or attack. Carew.
A seller of newspapers.
The clearstory, or upper story, of a building.
A thick loose woolen jacket, or coat, much worn by sailors in cold weather.
One who seeks out faults.
A stimulant, restorative, or tonic; a bracer. [Colloq.]
A stalk or shoot of sugar cane of the first growth from the cutting. The growth of the second and following years is of inferior quality, and is called rattoon.
A dish of broth, meat, and vegetables prepared by boiling in a pot, -- a dish esp. common among the French.  Grant Allen.
An iron bar made at a single heat from a puddle-ball hammering and rolling.
A man who is engaged in quarrying stones; a quarrier.
One of two suspending posts in a roof truss, or other framed truss of similar form. See King-post.
A show carried about in a box; a peep show. Pope.
A mantis.
The European red band fish, or fireflame. See Rend fish.
Strict adherence to official formalities. J. C. Shairp.
One who is tenacious of a strict adherence to official formalities. Ld. Lytton.
Money anciently paid by servile tenants to their lord, in lieu of the customary service of reaping his corn or grain.
Tumultuous festivity; revelry. [Obs.] Rowe.
A rabble; a riotous assembly; a mob. [Obs.]
Any one of numerous species of small white polished marine shells of the genus Olivella.

A name given to several different silver coins of Denmark, Holland, Sweden,, NOrway, etc., varying in value from about 30 cents to $1.10; also, a British coin worth about 36 cents, used in Ceylon and at the Cape of Good Hope. See Rigsdaler, Riksdaler, and Rixdaler.
A kind of pudding made of paste spread with fruit, rolled into a cylindrical form, and boiled or steamed.  -- a.
Shaped like a rolly-poly; short and stout. [Written also roly- poly.]
A whitlow running around the finger nail, but not affecting the bone. [Colloq.]
See Sanctus bell, under Sanctus.
Freedom from agitation or excitement of mind; coolness in trying circumstances; indifference; calmness. Burke.
, a. Cruising at random on the ocean.
The abuse of one's own self, powers, or faculties.
Self-deception; delusion. [Obs.] Shak.
Masturbation; onanism; self-pollution.
A color not mixed or variegated.
Faith in one's self; self-reliance.
Wrong done by a person himself. Shak.

A member of a branch of the Arians which did not acknowledge the Son to be consubstantial with the Father, that is, of the same substance, but admitted him to be of a like substance with the Father, not by nature, but by a peculiar privilege.
, a. Having no shell. J. Burroughs.
A hole for looking through; a peephole. "Stop all sight-holes." Shak.
One given to seeing sights or noted things, or eager for novelties or curiosities.
Distance to which the sight can reach or be thrown. [R.] Cowley.
One who is six feet tall. [Colloq. U.S.]

Any species of Pleurotomaria, a genus of beautiful, pearly, spiral gastropod shells having a deep slit in the outer lip. Many fossil species are known, and a few living ones are found in deep water in tropical seas.
Snow and water mixed, or snow just melted; very cold liquor. Shak.
The husband of one's daughter; a man in his relationship to his wife's parents. To take me as for thy son in lawe. Chaucer.
Poison spittle; poison ejected from the mouth. [R.] Hooker.
A california market fish (Pogonichthys macrolepidotus) belonging to the Carp family.
The pintail duck.
Food that is, or must be, taken with a spoon; liquid food. "Diet most upon spoon-meats." Harvey.

A gold coin, first made in the reign of Edward IV., having a star on the reverse resembling the rowel of a spur. In the reigns of Elizabeth and of James I., its value was fifteen shillings. [Written also spur-rial, and spur-ryal.]
Any one of several species of handsome gastropod shells of the genus Trochus, or Imperator. The shell is conical, with the margin toothed somewhat like the rowel of a spur.
An eye that squints. Spenser.
One who stands near; one who is present; a bystander.
A plant (Echinospermum Lappula) of the Borage family, with small blue flowers and prickly nutlets.

A hunting for game in a quiet and cautious manner, or under cover; stalking; hence, colloquially, the pursuit of any object quietly and cautiously.  -- Still"-hunt`er, n.  -- Still"-hunt`ing, n. [U.S.]
Tobacco which has been stripped of its stalks before packing.
A stallion, esp. one kept for breeding.

A prefix (also used adjectively) denoting the combination of constituents (especially electro-negative and electro-positive bodies) in the proportion of two to three; as, a subsesqui acetate, i. e., a salt having two equivalents of acetic acid to three of the base.
A circle or cluster of gas-burners for lighting and ventilating public buildings.
A broad, level, elevated area of land; a plateau. The toppling crags of Duty scaled, Are close upon the shining table- lands To which our God himself is moon and sun. Tennyson.
The parry which is connected with a riposte; also, a series of quick attacks and parries in which neither fencer gains a point.
Water in a tailrace.
Removal; murder. See To take off (c), under Take, v. t. The deep damnation of his taking-off. Shak.
A name given to several species of plants of the genus Polygonum, having angular stems beset with minute reflexed prickles.
A small saucer in which a teacup is set.
The opening in the furnaces through which fuel is introduced.
A workingmen's resort conducted under religious influences as a counteractant to the drinking saloon. [Colloq. or Cant]
A knocking down of all ten pins at one delivery of the ball. [U. S.]
Any quick, decisive stroke or act. [Colloq. U.S.]
See Terre-tenant.
A stone curlew. See under Stone.
An old name for the finest and most costly kind of velvet, having a fine, thick pile. I have served Prince Florizel and in my time wore three-pile. Shak.
Same as Tiger's-foot.

A tabular statement of the time at which, or within which, several things are to take place, as the recitations in a school, the departure and arrival of railroad trains or other public conveyances, the rise and fall of the tides, etc.

A plane surface divided in one direction with lines representing hours and minutes, and in the other with lines representing miles, and having diagonals (usually movable strings) representing the speed and position of various trains.
A table showing the notation, length, or duration of the several notes.
A lady's maid. Fashionableness of the tire-woman's making. Locke.
A dresser in a theater. Simmonds.
The page of a book which contains it title. The world's all title-page; there's no contents. Young.
A great talker. [Obs.]
Impeded motion of the tongue because of the shortness of the frænum, or of the adhesion of its margins to the gums. Dunglison.

The upper rigging, spars, etc., of a ship. [Written also top hamper.] All the ships of the fleet . . . were so encumbered with tophamper, so overweighted in proportion to their draught of water, that they could bear but little canvas, even with smooth seas and light and favorable winds. Motley.
A tackle used in hoisting and lowering the topmast.
See Tough-pitch (b).
The ruddy duck. [ Local U.S. ]
A town officer who makes proclamations to the people; the public crier of a town.
A towing path.
A peculiar distinguishing mark or device affixed by a manufacturer or a merchant to his goods, the exclusive right of using which is recognized by law.
An honest fellow. Shak. Bacon.
An instrument used by carpenters, joiners, etc., for laying off right angles off right angles, and testing whether work is square.
Any bivalve mollusk which secretes a shelly tube around its siphon, as the watering-shell.
A kind of fungus with an irregularly wrinkled, somewhat globular pileus (Helvella, or Gyromitra, esculenta.).
See 2d Tusk, n., 2.
A vagabond musician. [Obs.] You are an ass, a twire-pipe. Beau. & Fl. You looked like Twire-pipe, the taborer. Chapman.
A vessel of war carrying guns on two decks.
The agile gibbon; -- called also ungka-pati, and ungka-etam. See Gibbon.
A yellow, earthy incrustation, consisting essentially of the oxide of uranium, but more or less impure.
Any tropical humming bird of the genus Petasophora, having violet or purplish ear tufts.
A very handsome American butterfly (Polygonia interrogationis). Its wings are mottled with various shades of red and brown and have violet tips.
One bound by the same vow as another. [R.] Shak.
One who moves or wears a halter; one likely to be hanged. [Colloq. & Obs.] I can tell you, I am a mad wag-halter. Marston.
Any of several plants bearing thorns or stiff hooked appendages, which catch and tear the clothing, as:
The greenbrier.
Any of various species of hawthorn.
In South Africa, one of numerous acacias and mimosas.
The grapple plant.
The prickly ash.
Any plant of the genus Arum, especially, in England, the cuckoopint (Arum maculatum).
An American fresh-water mussel (Quadrula pustulosa). Its shell is used in making buttons.
A stubble goose. [Obs. or Prov. Eng.]
An annual feast of the persons employed in a printing office. [Written also way-goose.] [Eng.]
The state or condition of being well; welfare; happiness; prosperity; as, virtue is essential to the well-being of men or of society.
A white mark in the forehead of a horse, descending almost to the nose; -- called also white-blaze.
A white mark on the foot of a horse, between the fetlock and the coffin.
A broad-brimmed, low-crowned felt hat.
A low, narrowleaved evergreen shrub (Cneorum tricoccon) found in Southern Europe.
A clump of trees serving for a protection against the force of wind. [Local, U. S.]
A windflower.
Any one of various species of marine bivalve shells belonging to the genus Avicula, in which the hinge border projects like a wing.
Any marine gastropod shell of the genus Strombus. See Strombus.
Any pteropod shell.
The witch-hazel.
A leguminous plant (Genista tinctoria) of Europe and Russian Asia, and adventitious in America; -- called also greenwood, greenweed, dyer's greenweed, and whin, wood-wash, wood-wax, and wood- waxen.
A young oak, or other timber plant, laid down in a hedge among the whitethorn or other plants used in hedges.
Any species of Vermetus.
Same as Wringbolt.
The wych-elm; -- so called because its leaves are like those of the hazel.
See Veda.
One of a set of vagabonds who formerly roamed through England, feigning lunacy for the sake of obtaining alms. Nares. To sham Abraham, to feign sickness. Goldsmith.
One of the sessile cirripeds; a barnacle of the genus Balanus. See Barnacle.
A foolish or dull-witted fellow. [Colloq.]
The impression of a vivid sensation retained by the retina of the eye after the cause has been removed; also extended to impressions left of tones, smells, etc.
The sails on the mizzenmast, or on the stays between the mainmast and mizzenmast. Totten.
An officer selected by a general to carry orders, also to assist or represent him in correspondence and in directing movements.
The hold or grip of an anchor, or that to which it holds.
Hence: Firm hold: security.
A Saxon of Britain, that is, an English Saxon, or one the Saxons who settled in England, as distinguished from a continental (or "Old") Saxon.

The Teutonic people (Angles, Saxons, Jutes) of England, or the English people, collectively, before the Norman Conquest. It is quite correct to call Æthelstan "King of the Anglo-Saxons," but to call this or that subject of Æthelstan "an Anglo-Saxon" is simply nonsense. E. A. Freeman.
The language of the English people before the Conquest (sometimes called Old English). See Saxon.
One of the race or people who claim descent from the Saxons, Angles, or other Teutonic tribes who settled in England; a person of English descent in its broadest sense.

A proclamation, as of the French kings, calling not only their immediate feudatories, but the vassals of these feudatories, to take the field for war; also, the body of vassals called or liable to be called to arms, as in ancient France.
A furnace or oven for fritting materials for glass making.
The van or advanced body of an army. See Vanguard.
An ornament resembling a ball placed in a circular flower, the petals of which form a cup round it, -- usually inserted in a hollow molding.
Liquor made from barley; strong ale. [Humorous] [Scot.] Burns.
A furnace or stove in which the fuel is contained in a hopper or chamber, and is fed to the fire as the lower stratum is consumed.
Some as Bas-relief.
A species of hellebore (Helleborus foetidus), with digitate leaves. It has an offensive smell and acrid taste, and is a powerful emetic, cathartic, and anthelmintic.
The molding of a cornice immediately below the corona. Oxf. Gloss.
Stupid; dull. Shak.
A kind or favorable reception or salutation. [Obs.]
A love letter or note. A lover chanting out a billet-doux. Spectator.
A molding whose section is thought to resemble a beak.

A papilionaceous plant, the Ornithopus, having a curved, cylindrical pod tipped with a short, clawlike point. Bird's-foot trefoil. (Bot.) (a) A genus of plants (Lotus) with clawlike pods. L. corniculatas, with yellow flowers, is very common in Great Britain.
the related plant, Trigonella ornithopodioides, is also European.

A law enacted to provide for the regulation and supervision of investment companies in order to protect the public against companies that do not intend to do a fair and honest business and that offer investments that do not promise a fair return; -- so called because the promises made by some investment companies are as boundless or alluring as the blue sky, or, perhaps, because designed to clear away the clouds and fogs from the simple investor's horizon. [Colloq.]
A cetacean of the Dolphin family, of several species, as Delphinus Tursio and Lagenorhyncus leucopleurus, of Europe.
The puffin.
Words that rhyme, proposed as the ends of verses, to be filled out by the ingenuity of the person to whom they are offered.
An arcograph.
A small pair of compasses, one leg of which carries a pencil, or a pen, for drawing circles. Its legs are often connected by a bow- shaped spring, instead of by a joint.
A pair of compasses, with a bow or arched plate riveted to one of the legs, and passing through the other.
A bridge keeper; a warden or a guard for a bridge. [Obs.] Sir W. Scott.
The principal ward of a key. Knight.
A basket in which clothes are carried to the wash. Shak.
A plant with leaves branched somewhat like a buck's horn (Plantago Coronopus); also, Lobelia coronopifolia.
A corm.
A nail with a round head and short shank, tinned and lacquered.

A contrivance consisting of a slat of wood tied to the end of a thong or string, with which the slat is whirled so as to cause an intermittent roaring noise. It is used as a toy, and among some races in certain religious rites.
An external angle when obtuse or rounded.
A drinking between meals. [Obs.]
An election held by itself, not at the time of a general election.
Self-interest; private advantage. Atterbury.
See under Calcite.
A cistern or vault at the point where a street gutter discharges into a sewer, to oatch bulky matters which would not pass readly throught the sewer. Knight.
One of the short ropes or iron cramps used to brace in the shrouds toward the masts so a to give freer sweep to the yards.
A long, light, open vehicle, with benches or seats running lengthwise.
See Chasse, n., above.
The wild service of Europe (Purus torminalis).
A species of European warbler (Sylvia hippolais); -- called also chip-chap, and pettychaps.
A strap leading from the bellyband to the lower part of the collar, to keep the collar in place.
A lively dance (called also galliard), the steps of which were regulated by the number five. [Obs.] Nares. Shak.
A utensil to hold a chamber vessel, for the use of the sick and infirm. It is usually in the form of a box, with a seat and tight cover.
A sudden copious rainfall, as the whole cloud had been precipitated at once.
A joint assessor.
See Lumpfish. [Scot.]
A narrow chisel adapted for cutting a groove. Knight.
A red nose. Shak.
Corresponding relation.
One who suffers with another. Wycherley.
The wheel in a clock which regulates the number of strokes.
Any position giving the enemy such advantage that the troops occupying it must either surrender or be cut to pieces. Farrow.
An inferior court of civil jurisdiction, attached to a manor, and held by the steward; a baron's court; -- now fallen into disuse.
The artifices, intrigues, and plottings, at courts.
The fielder in the games of cricket and lacrosse who supports "point."
Something used to conceal infamy. [Obs.] Dryden.
A plant of Sierra Leone which yields a wholesome, creamy juice.
A wooden knife with a long thin blade, used in handling cream or ice cream.
Same as Cribbing, 4.
Any preternatural labor, in whiche the boly of the child lies across the pelvis of the mother, so that the shoulder, arm, or trunk is the part first presented at the mouth of the uterus.
One of the temporary wooden braces, placed horizontally across a frame to hold it in position until the deck beams are in; a cross- pawl.
An instrument formerly used at sea for taking the altitudes of celestial bodies.
A surveyor's instrument for measuring offsets.
See Harmotome, and Staurotide.
The wrinkles that appear, as the effect of age or dissipation, under and around the outer corners of the eyes. Tennyson.
A caltrop. [Written also crowfoot.]
Same as Bird's-mouth. [U.S.]
A box or perch near the top of a mast, esp. in whalers, to shelter the man on the lookout.
A slovenly woman; a slattern; a draggle-tail.
One who works by the day; -- usually applied to a farm laborer, or to a workman who does not work at any particular trade. Goldsmith.
The condition of being a deaf-mute.
Peninsula. [Obs.] Knolles.
A small water bird. See Dabchick.
A small annual species of Geranium, native in England; -- so called from the shape of the leaf.
The columbine. [Prov. Eng.] Halliwell.
The May apple (Podophyllum peltatum).
A framework on which dishes, food, etc., are passed from one room or story of a house to another; a lift for dishes, etc.; also, a piece of furniture with movable or revolving shelves.
The earwig.
The loon or great northern diver. See Loon. [Written also emmer-goose and imber-goose.]
A block, or ring, serving as a guide for the running rigging or for any rope.
The upper stomach of a cow, or other ruminant animal; the rumen.
Feverfew.
A nonsensical exclamation attributed to giants and ogres; hence, any expression calculated to impose upon the timid and ignorant. "Impudent fee-faw-fums." J. H. Newman.
Any small windowlike opening or recess, esp. one to show the relics within an altar, or the like.
A tackle or purchase used to raise the flukes of the anchor up to the gunwale. The block used is called the fish-block.
See Cinquefoil.
A starfish with five rays, esp. Asterias rubens.

A small beetle of the family Halticidæ, of many species. They have strong posterior legs and leap like fleas. The turnip flea- beetle (Phyllotreta vittata) and that of the grapevine (Graptodera chalybea) are common injurious species.

The distance to which an arrow or flight may be shot; bowshot, -- about the fifth of a mile. [Prov. Eng. & Scot.] Within a flight-shot it inthe valley. Evelyn. Half a flight-shot from the king's oak. Sir W. Scott.
One of those who went to California in the rush for gold in 1849; an argonaut. [Colloq., U. S.]
A large bedstead with tall posts at the corners to support curtains. [Colloq.]
The liberty or franchise of having a chase; free chase. Burrill.
Unrestrained indulgence of the appetites.
An imperfect female calf, twinborn with a male.
A plant of the genus Atriplex; orache. Gray.
The lamb's-quarters (Chenopodium album). Dr. Prior.
The European green woodpecker; also, the spotted woodpecker. [Prov. Eng.]
A chilognath myriapod of the genus Iulus, and allied genera, having numerous short legs along the sides; a milliped or "thousand legs." See Chilognatha.
The common English milkwort (Polygala vulgaris), so called from blossoming in gang week. Dr. Prior.
The office of a gauger.
Same as Guelder-rose.
The gyrfalcon.
A small, transparent, land snail, of the genus Vitrina.

A long, footless lizard (Ophiosaurus ventralis), of the Southern United States; -- so called from its fragility, the tail easily breaking into small pieces. It grows to the length of three feet. The name is applied also to similar species found in the Old World.
The yellow-hammer.
A plant of the genus Genista (G. tinctoria); dyer's weed; -- called also greenweed.
A stall at which greens and fresh vegetables are exposed for sale.
Artificial and ornamental rockwork in imitation of a grotto. Cowper.
An intimate companion. Hail-fellow well met. Lyly.
See Forkbeard.
A sister by one parent only.
A jury, for the trial of a fore foreigner, composed equally of citizens and aliens.
A term of reproach, implying that one is fit to be hanged. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.

A member of one description of roof truss, called hammer-beam truss, which is so framed as not to have a tiebeam at the top of the wall. Each principal has two hammer-beams, which occupy the situation, and to some extent serve the purpose, of a tiebeam.
A child's play, one child guessing in which closed hand the other holds some small object, winning the object if right and forfeiting an equivalent if wrong; hence, forfeit. Piers Plowman.
A kind of grass (Eriophorum vaginatum). See Cotton grass, under Cotton. Hare's-tail grass (Bot.), a species of grass (Lagurus ovatus) whose head resembles a hare's tail.
A common British fern (Scolopendrium vulgare), rare in America.
A West Indian fern, the Polypodium Phyllitidis of Linnæus. It is also found in Florida.
A dish made of portions of the head, or head and feet, of swine, cut up fine, seasoned, and pressed into a cheeselike mass.

A member of any tribe or race of savages who have the custom of decapitating human beings and preserving their heads as trophies. The Dyaks of Borneo are the most noted head-hunters.  -- Head"-hunt`ing, n.
A part of the breastbone. [Obs.] He feeleth through the herte-spon the pricke. Chaucer.
The flicker; -- called also high-hole. [Local, U. S.]
The upper terminal pipe of a mining pump. Raymond.
The for pump in the pit. Raymond.
Return home. Kepeth this child, al be it foul or fayr, And eek my wyf, unto myn hoom-cominge. Chaucer.
A large blood-sucking leech (Hæmopsis vorax), of Europe and Northern Africa. It attacks the lips and mouths of horses.
A farrier; a veterinary surgeon.

A stringled instrument, lutelike in shape, in which the sound is produced by the friction of a wheel turned by a crank at the end, instead of by a bow, two of the strings being tuned as drones, while two or more, tuned in unison, are modulated by keys.
In California, a water wheel with radial buckets, driven by the impact of a jet.
Tumult; bustle; confusion. Shak. All places were filled with tumult and hurly-burly. Knolles.
An ideo-motor movement.
The loon. See Ember-goose.
A person born in India, of mixed Indian and British blood; a half-caste. Malcom.
A combining from (also used adjectively), signifying: Pertaining to, or designating, the characteristic, nitrogenous radical, NOH, called the isonitroso group.
A small stuffed puppet to be pelted in Lent; hence, a simple fellow.
A large clavate spine of a fossil sea urchin.
See St. John's-wort.
See Gillyflower.
A gallant who captivates the hearts of women. "A renowned dandy and lady-killer." Blackw. Mag.
Indian cress.
A tapster. [Obs.]
An Australian myrtaceous tree (Eugenia Smithii), having smooth ovate leaves, and panicles of small white flowers. The wood is hard and fine-grained.
An old slang name for the pillory, stocks, etc., of a prison.[Eng.] Latimer.
The wryneck.
One who ate the fruit or leaf of the lotus, and, as a consequence, gave himself up to indolence and daydreams; one of the Lotophagi. The mild-eyed melancholy Lotos-eaters. Tennyson.
Courtship. Bacon.
The dagger held in the left hand, while the rapier is held in the right; -- used to parry thrusts of the adversary's rapier.
A hamper to be carried in the hand; a hand basket used in carrying grapes to the press.
A feigning to believe; make believe. J. H. Newman.
A tool somewhat like a chisel with a groove in it, used by calkers of ships to finish the seams after the oakum has been driven in.
A supposed discovery which turns out to be a hoax; something grosaly absurd.
A long streaky cloud, spreading out like a horse's tail, and believed to indicate rain; a cirrus cloud. See Cloud. Mackerel sky and mare's-tails Make tall ships carry low sails. Old Rhyme.
An aquatic plant of the genus Hippuris (H.vulgaris), having narrow leaves in whorls.
A coarse cloth.
One whose motive is to please men or the world, rather than God. Eph. vi. 6.
The master or superintendent of a mint. Also used figuratively.
A figure which strikes the hour on the bell of some fanciful clocks; -- called also jack of the clock house.
A timeserver; an inconstant person. Shak.
One who coins or prints money; also, a counterfeiter of money. [R.]
One who accumulates money or wealth; specifically, one who makes money-getting his governing motive.
A Moorish pike. [Obs.]
Talk or writing which is weakly sentimental or affectedly pretty. Macaulay.
The modern Hebrew language.
An adherent of Neo-Kantianism.
A beautiful black marble found in fragments among Roman ruins, and usually thought to have come from ancient Laconia.
A circular letter, written or printed for the purpose of disseminating news. This was the name given to the earliest English newspapers.
One who gathered news for, and wrote, news-letters. Macaulay.
The northern butcher bird.
The goat's beard, whose flowers close at midday.
The condition or characteristics of an old maid. G. Eliot.
A patient who is outside a hospital, but receives medical aid from it.
An order passed from front to rear by word of mouth.
A pointed beard. [Obs.]
The willet.
The course of plank laid horizontally over the timberheads of a vessel's frame.
The white spot on a target, at which an arrow or other missile is aimed. [Obs.] Jonson.
With all small arms, the second point in which the natural line of sight, when horizontal, cuts the trajectory.
With artillery, the point where the projectile first strikes the horizontal plane on which the gun stands, the axis of the piece being horizontal.
The bar-tailed godwit. [Prov. Eng.]
A ridge within and behind the tragus in the ear of some animals.
A small British and American pond snail (Bulinus hypnorum).

A drink served after coffee at dinner, usually one of several liqueurs, or cordials, of different specific gravities poured so as to remain separate in layers; hence, such a drink of cordials served at any time.
The first coating of plaster in work of three coats upon laths. Its surface is scratched once to form a better key for the next coat. In the United States called scratch coat. Brande & C.
The book used by a prompter of a theater.
A memorandum of a sale, and time when payment is due, given to the purchaser at a sale of goods.
An aërial corm, or thickened stem, as of some epiphytic orchidaceous plants.
One of the soft gelatinous cones found in the compound eyes of certain insects, taking the place of the crystalline cones of others.
The lump of pasty wrought iron as taken from the puddling furnace to be hammered or rolled.
A tumultuous crowd; a rabble; a noisy throng.
Any one of several species of humming birds of the genus Steganura, having two of the tail feathers very long and racket- shaped.
One who is subjected to playing rack-rent.
One who exacts rack-rent.
A forming anew; a new creation or formation.
A forming anew; a new creation or formation.
The act of redeeming, or the state of being redeemed; repurchase; ransom; release; rescue; deliverance; as, the redemption of prisoners taken in war; the redemption of a ship and cargo. Specifically:
A European leguminous plant (Ononis arvensis) with long, tough roots.

A turning directly about by the right, so as to face in the opposite direction; also, the quarter directly opposite; as, to turn to the right-about. To send to the right-about, to cause to turn toward the opposite point or quarter; -- hence, of troops, to cause to turn and retreat. [Colloq.] Sir W. Scott.
A cylindrical piece of wood or other material, with which paste or dough may be rolled out and reduced to a proper thickness.
A game in which a ball, rolling into a certain place, wins. [Written also rouly-pouly.]
The first coat of plaster laid on brick; also, the process of applying it.
See Rolly-pooly.
A stickler for rules; a slave of rules [R.] Hare.
A surety for the appearance of a person at a given time. Bracton.
The edible fruit of the Gaultheria Shallon, an ericaceous shrub found from California northwards. The berries are about the size of a common grape and of a dark purple color.
Jack-by-the-hedge. See under Jack.
the wheel in an escapement (as of a clock or a watch) into the teeth of which the pallets play.
A jellyfish.
One who contrives to give himself vexation. [Archaic.] Sir P. Sidney.
Action by, or originating in, one's self or itself.
A reaping machine containing mechanism for binding the grain into sheaves.
The act of deceiving one's self, or the state of being self- deceived; self-deception.
The denial of one's self; forbearing to gratify one's own desires; self-sacrifice.
The holding a good opinion of one's self; self-complacency.
Inborn mettle or courage; one's own temper. [Obs.] Shak.
Motion given by inherent power, without external impulse; spontaneus or voluntary motion. Matter is not induced with self-motion. Cheyne.
Praise of one's self.
One who seeks only his own interest, advantage, or pleasure.
A gazogene.
A relay apparatus; specif.:

An auxiliary motor, regulated by a hand lever, for quickly and easily moving the reversing gear of a large marine engine into any desired position indicated by that of the hand lever, which controls the valve of the motor.
In a Whitehead torpedo, a compressed-air motor, for moving the rudders so as to correct deviations from the course.
See Shadbird (a)
A lake whitefish; the roundfish. See Roundfish.
Shameless. Shak.
A modest, diffident look; a loving glance; -- commonly in the plural. I saw her just now give him the languishing eye, as they call it; . . . of old called the sheep's-eye. Wycherley.
A variety of calcite, so called from its slaty structure; -- called also slate spar.
A taking sides, as with a party, sect, or faction. Bp. Hall.

An irregular gait of a horse; -- called also single-footed pace. See Single, v. i. Single-foot is an irregular pace, rather rare, distinguished by the posterior extremities moving in the order of a fast walk, and the anterior extremities in that of a slow trot. Stillman (The Horse in Motion.)
A pistol or other firearm which can be fired six times without reloading especially, a six-chambered revolver. [Colloq. U.S.]
The piked dogfish.
A dark bluish gray color.
One who is apt to find and frequent good tables; a parasite; a sponger. The epicure and the smell-feast. South.
A feast at which the guests are supposed to feed upon the odors only of the viands.
A sounding-board. To many a row of pipes the sound-board breathes. Milton.
A channel at the end of a deck to restrain the water.
A young chicken before it is fully fledged. [Prov. Eng.]
Having the toe square. Obsolete as fardingales, ruffs, and square-toed shoes. V. Knox.
A precise person; -- used contemptuously or jocularly. Thackeray.
A covering or protection, as a canvas, for a stack.
A stem-winding watch. [Colloq.]
Beggar's ticks.
Stallion. [Obs.] Mortimer.
A building in which sugar is made or refined; a sugar manufactory.
A climbing shrub (Berchemia volubilus) of the Southern United States, having a tough and pliable stem.

A somewhat similar tropical American plant (Paullinia Curassavica); also, a walking stick made from its stem. He was in form and spirit like a supple-jack, . . . yielding, but tough; though he bent, he never broke. W. Irving.
The cartilaginous cap at the sacral end of the ilium of some animals.
The down, or fine, soft feathers, of the swan, used on various articles of dress.
A fine, soft, thick cloth of wool mixed with silk or cotton; a sort of twilled fustian, like moleskin. Swan's-down cotton. See Cotton flannel, under Cotton.
A yearly expedition on the Thames to take up young swans and mark them, as by Companies of Dyers and Vintners; -- called also swan-hopping. [Eng.] Encyc. Brit.
One who has a sickly, pale complexion. Shak.
The spotted sandpiper. See the Note under Sandpiper.
A plant, the star-of-Bethlehem. See under Star.
A large oceanic fish (Elops saurus) found in the tropical parts of all the oceans. It is used chiefly for bait.
An olive-green earth used as a pigment. See Glauconite.
Private conversation; familiar interview or conference of two persons.
A short sofa intended to accomodate two persons.

A game played with rackets and a ball suspended by a string from an upright pole, the object of each side being to wrap the string around the pole by striking the ball in a direction opposite to the other.
A third part of the profits of fines and penalties imposed at the country court, which was among the perquisites enjoyed by the earl.
Threshold. [Obs.] Chaucer.
An instrument used for twisting ropes out of straw.
A kind of carriage. See Whiskey. Southery.
The room or place where players dress for the stage.
The highest timbers on the side of a vessel, being those above the futtocks. R. H. Dana, Jr.
Paper steeped in saltpeter, which burns slowly, and is used as a match for firing gunpowder, and the like.
The exact state or quality of texture and consistency of well reduced and refined copper.
Copper so reduced; -- called also tough-cake.

An edible fish (Lobotes Surinamensis) found in the warmer parts of all the oceans, and common on the southern and middle coasts of the United States. When living it is silvery gray, and becomes brown or blackish when dead. Its dorsal and anal fins are long, and extend back on each side of the tail. It has large silvery scales which are used in the manufacture of fancy work. Called also, locally, black perch, grouper, and flasher.
A low bed on wheels, that may be pushed under another bed; a trundle-bed. "His standing bed and truckle-bed." Shak.
A low bed that is moved on trundles, or little wheels, so that it can be pushed under a higher bed; a truckle-bed; also, sometimes, a simiral bed without wheels. Chapman.
One who loves the truth. Truth-lover was our English Duke. Tennyson.
A silk fabric formerly in use, having a nap or pile. [Written also tuft-taffeta.]
A large, handsomely colored, marine univalve shell (Fasciolaria tulipa) native of the Southern United States. The name is sometimes applied also to other species of Fasciolaria.

An eccentric ragtime dance, danced with the feet well apart and with a characteristic rise on the ball of the foot, followed by a drop upon the heel. The original form, owning to the positions assumed by the dancers, is offensively suggestive. Similar dances are the bunny hug and grizzly bear, so called in allusion to the movements and the positions assumed by the partners in dancing.
The melon cactus. [West Indies]
Any of several species of Echinocactus. [California]
A long-handled, round-headed broom for sweeping ceilings, etc. [Colloq. or Dial.]
A loop or sleeve with a screw thread at one end and a swivel at the other, -- used for tightening a rod, stay, etc.
A gravitating catch, as for fastening a shutter, the end of a chain, or a hasp.
One who does tut-work. Tomlinson.
See Twelfthtide.
Any fresh-water gastropod of the genus Valvata.
One sent in advance; an avant-courier; a precursor.
A grand vizier. See under Vizier.
A light puff paste, with a raised border, filled, after baking, usually with a ragout of fowl, game, or fish.
One of the Australian wattle trees (Acacia colletioides), so called from the impenetrability of the thicket which it makes.
= Wait-a-bit.
A vinelike plant (Vitis Caribæa) growing in parched districts in the West Indies, and containing a great amount of sap which is sometimes used for quenching thirst.
A vinelike plant (Vitis Caribæa) growing in parched districts in the West Indies, and containing a great amount of sap which is sometimes used for quenching thirst.
A turn of the cable about the end of the windlass, without the bits.
Any one of numerous species of small marine bivalves belonging to Donax and allied genera in which the shell is wedge-shaped.
A building at or within which goods, and the like, are weighed.
One whose intention is good. "Well-meaners think no harm." Dryden.
One who wishes well, or means kindly. [R.] "A well-willer of yours." Brydges.
A whirling blast or wind. A whirl-blast from behind the hill. Wordsworth.
See White-face.
A somewhat heart-shaped cherry with a whitish skin.
A dangerous disease of sheep.
A young whiting. [Prov. Eng.]
A fair lass. "This pretty whiting-mop." Massinger.
One who makes widows by destroying husbands. [R.] Shak.

A perennial herb (Epilobium spicatum) with narrow willowlike leaves and showy rose-purple flowers. The name is sometimes made to include other species of the same genus. Spiked willow-herb, a perennial herb (Lythrum Salicaria) with willowy leaves and spiked purplish flowers.
A European species of loosestrife (Lysimachia vulgaris).
Any kind of Polygonum with willowlike foliage.
Same as Willow-weed.
Any plant of the order Salicaceæ, or the Willow family.
The kestrel. B. Jonson.
A rectangular rent made in cloth; -- called also winkle-hole. [Local, U. S.] Bartlett.
One who draws metal into wire.
One who pulls the wires, as of a puppet; hence, one who operates by secret means; an intriguer. Political wire-pullers and convention packers. Lowell.
One who manufactures articles from wire.
A weak or thin drink or liquor; wish-wash.
The wych-elm.
An American shrub or small tree (Hamamelis Virginica), which blossoms late in autumn.
One who breaks jests; a joker. [Obs.] Shak.
One who affects repartee; a wit-cracker. [Obs.] Shak.
A kind of club moss. See Lycopodium.
Club moss. See Lycopodium.
Any kind of spurge (Euphorbia); -- so called from its acrid milky juice.
A negro. [Low]
See Ihlang-ihlang.
The sacred writings of the ancient Persian religion, attributed to Zoroaster, but chiefly of a later date.
A member of the Bantu race comprising the Zulus and the Kaffirs.
The European siskin (Carduelis spinus), a small green and yellow finch, related to the goldfinch.
The largest hammer used by smiths. Weale.
The time just after dinner. "An after-dinner's sleep." Shak. [Obs.] -- a.
Following dinner; post-prandial; as, an after-dinner nap.
Aftergrass.
A fleecy cloud formation consisting of large whitish or grayish globular cloudlets with shaded  portions, often grouped in flocks or rows.
Alto-rilievo.
High relief; sculptured work in which the figures project more than half their thickness; as, this figure is an alto-rilievo or in alto-rilievo.
A cloud formation similar to cirro-stratus, but heavier and at a lower level.
A pimp; a kept gallant. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.
One who carries the armor or arms of another; an armiger. Judg. ix. 54.
A soldier belonging to the irregular troops of the Turkish army.
An interior acrow's-foot in the United States.
A bishop's seat or see.
Dull; stupid. Blunt-witted lord, ignoble in demeanor! Shak.
A modern reforming theistic sect among the Hindos. [Written also Brahma-samaj.]
The state of privilege of a burgess. South.
The guard or defense of a castle.
A tax or imposition an a dwelling within a certain distance of a castle, for the purpose of maintaining watch and ward in it; castle-ward.
A feudal tenure, obliging the tenant to perform service within the realm, without limitation of time.
meadow irrigated by water from a spring or rivulet on the side of hill.
A remote relation. See Quater-cousin. Shak.
Cavo-rilievo.
Hollow relief; sculpture in relief within a sinking made for the purpose, so no part of it projects beyond the plain surface around.
A French coasting lugger.

The killing of a person in an affray, in the heat of blood, and while under the influence of passion, thus distinguished from chance- medley or killing in self-defense, or in a casual affray. Burrill.
A seat in the porch of a church. Shak.
Blockhead; dunce; -- so called because the handle of a cittern usually ended with a carved head. Marsion
See Chiaroscuro.
A secret society of Irish Fenians founded in Philadelphia in 1881.
Barriers with loopholes, formerly erected on the deck of a vessel to shelter the men in a close engagement with an enemy's boarders; -- called also close quarters. [Obs.]
One who raises coal out of the hold of a ship. [Eng.] Dickens.
A telescope of low power, having a large field of view, used for finding comets.
A cheat; a sharper; a deceiver. [Obs.] Minsheu.
A created or high-topped crown or head. "Like the copple-crown the lapwing has." T. Randolph.  -- Cop"ple-crowned`, a.
A horizontal row of corbels, with the panels or filling between them; also, less properly used to include the stringcourse on them.
A duplicate roll (record or account) kept by an officer as a check upon another officer's roll. Burrill.
Same as Prison base.

A diminutive of the chevron, containing one fourth of its surface. Couple-closes are generally borne one on each side of a chevron, and the blazoning may then be either a chevron between two couple-closes or chevron cottised.
A pair of rafters framed together with a tie fixed at their feet, or with a collar beam. [Engl.]
The geranium; -- so named from the long axis of the fruit, which resembles the beak of a crane. Dr. Prior.
A pair of long-beaked forceps.
A subdeacon who bears a cross before an archbishop or primate on solemn occasions.
A hinge having one strap perpendicular and the other strap horizontal giving it the form of an Egyptian or T cross.
A form of stitch, where the stitches are diagonal and in pairs, the thread of one stitch crossing that of the other. "Tent and cross- stitch." Sir W. Scott.  -- Cross"-stitch`, v. t. & i.
A mode of harrowing crosswise, or transversely to the ridges. Crabb.

A naked human skull as the emblem of death; the head of the conventional personification of death. I had rather be married to a death's-head with a bone in his mouth. Shak. Death's-head moth (Zoöl.), a very large European moth (Acherontia atropos), so called from a figure resembling a human skull on the back of the thorax; -- called also death's-head sphinx.
The deadly nightshade (Atropa belladonna). Dr. Prior.
Half relief; sculpture in relief of which the figures project from the background by one half their full roundness.
A work of sculpture of the above character. See Alto-rilievo.
The salt-marsh terrapin of the Atlantic coast (Malacoclemmys palustris).
Hound's-tongue.
A locomotive with pilot at each end. Knight.
Double-quick time, step, or march.
A draggle-tail; a slattern. Halliwell.
A slattern who suffers her gown to trail in the mire; a drabble-tail.
A room appropriated for the reception of company; a room to which company withdraws from the dining room.

The company assembled in such a room; also, a reception of company in it; as, to hold a drawing-room. He [Johnson] would amaze a drawing-room by suddenly ejaculating a clause of the Lord's Prayer. Macaulay. Drawing-room car. See Palace car, under Car.
A fungus of the genus Geoglossum.

A style of engraving in relief by means of voltaic electricity. A picture is drawn on a metallic plate with some material which resists the fluids of a battery; so that, in electro-typing, the parts not covered by the varnish, etc., receive a deposition of metal, and produce the required copy in intaglio. A cast of this is then the plate for printing.
One who makes a practice off discovering others' faults and censuring them; a scold.
A second raampart, exterior to, and parallel to, the main rampart, and considerably below its level.
The thin, new growth around the edge of a shell, of an oyster.
Any thin, as on a board or a razor.
An aquatic plant (Hottonia palustris), having finely divided leaves.
A frivolous or featherbrained person. [Colloq.] H. James.
A large, venomous serpent (Trigonocephalus lanceolatus) of Brazil and the West Indies. It is allied to the rattlesnake, but has no rattle.
The iris. See Flower-de-luce.

A conventional flower suggested by the iris, and having a form which fits it for the terminal decoration of a scepter, the ornaments of a crown, etc. It is also a heraldic bearing, and is identified with the royal arms and adornments of France.

A tropical leguminous bush (Poinciana, or Cæsalpinia, pulcherrima) with prickly branches, and showy yellow or red flowers; -- so named from its having been sometimes used for hedges in the West Indies. Baird.
The mast erected at the head of the foremast, and at the head of which stands the fore-topgallant mast. See Ship.
See Sail.

A plant of the genus Mirabilis. There are about half a dozen species, natives of the warmer parts of America. The common four- o'clock is M. Jalapa. Its flowers are white, yellow, and red, and open toward sunset, or earlier in cloudy weather; hence the name. It is also called marvel of Peru, and afternoon lady.
The friar bird; -- so called from its cry, which resembles these words.
A vehicle having four wheels. [Colloq.]
A French partisan soldier, or one belonging to a corps of detached light troops engaged in forays, skirmishes, scouting, etc.
A beggar with a wallet; a licensed beggar. [Scot.] Sir W. Scott.
A small triangular sail having its foot extended upon the gaff and its luff upon the topmast.
A siliceous sponge, of the genus Hyalonema, and allied genera; -- so called from their glassy fibers or spicules; -- called also vitreous sponge. See Glass-rope, and Euplectella.
The art or process of reducing gold to extremely thin leaves, by beating with a hammer. Ure.
A pebble, or small fragment of stone; a calculus.

A concrete juice produced by various trees found in the Malayan archipelago, especially by the Isonandra, or Dichopsis, Gutta. It becomes soft, and unpressible at the tamperature of boiling water, and, on cooling, retains its new shape. It dissolves in oils and ethers, but not in water. In many of its properties it resembles caoutchouc, and it is extensively used for many economical purposes. The Mimusops globosa of Guiana also yields this material.
A brother by one parent, but not by both.
The gathering and bringing home of the harvest; the time of harvest. Showed like a stubble land at harvest-home. Shak.
The song sung by reapers at the feast made at the close of the harvest; the feast itself. Dryden.
A service of thanksgiving, at harvest time, in the Church of England and in the Protestant Episcopal Church in the United States.
The opportunity of gathering treasure. Shak.
A irrevocable Turkish decree countersigned by the sultan.
Ease of heart; peace or tranquillity of mind or feeling. Shak.
A species of violet (Viola tricolor); -- called also pansy.
A horse that moves with a high step or proud gait; hence, a person having a proud bearing. [Colloq.]
One who speaks in public; an haranguer; a preacher. Addison.
A staying at home.
A dose of physic for a horse. Shak.
The appliance by which the dose is administred.
A professional rider and trainer of race horses.
A trainer and dealer in horses.
A carriage hung on poles, and borne by and between two horses. Milton.

A plant of the genus Nasturtium (N. Armoracia), allied to scurvy grass, having a root of a pungent taste, much used, when grated, as a condiment and in medicine. Gray. Horse-radish tree. (Bot.) See Moringa.
The character, personality, or office of a hostess. Shak.
A worthless dog that runs back on the scent; a blunderer. [Obs.] Shak.
A little dandy; a little, foppish, impertinent fellow.
A silly, pert girl; -- corresponding to jackanapes. Massinger.

A member of a secret political organization in the United States, the chief objects of which were the proscription of foreigners by the repeal of the naturalization laws, and the exclusive choice of native Americans for office.
The art or practice of captivating the hearts of women. Better for the sake of womankind that this dangerous dog should leave off lady-killing. Thackeray.
See Lake dwellers, under Lake.
Taking of leave; parting compliments. Shak.

A general name for a group of Algonquin tribes which formerly occupied the coast region of North America from Connecticut to Virginia. They included the Mohicans, Delawares, Shawnees, and several other tribes.
See Leze majesty.
An abject flatterer or parasite. Theodore Hook.

A tree (Guaiacum officinale) found in the warm latitudes of America, from which the guaiacum of medicine is procured. Its wood is very hard and heavy, and is used for various mechanical purposes, as for the wheels of ships' blocks, cogs, bearings, and the like. See Guaiacum.
A plant (Sedum Telephium) with fleshy leaves, which has extreme powers of resisting drought; garden ox-pine.
The Canada lynx. See Lynx.
A feigning to believe, as in the play of children; a mere pretense; a fiction; an invention. "Childlike make-believe." Tylor. To forswear self-delusion and make-believe. M. Arnold.
One whose business is to make sport for others; a buffoon; a zany; especially, one who attends a mountebank or quack doctor.
The world, considered as lying between heaven and hell. [Obs.] Shak.
The act or process of making money; the acquisition and accumulation of wealth. Obstinacy in money-making. Milman.
The fruit of the Adansonia digitata; also, the tree. See Adansonia.
A kind of easy-chair with a back which may be lowered or raised.
The umbilical cord.
An adherent of Neo-Hegelianism.
Same as Romaic.
An omission or neglect to do something, esp. that which ought to have been done. Cf. Malfeasance.
A favorite Spanish dish, consisting of a mixture of several kinds of meat chopped fine, and stewed with vegetables.
Any incongruous mixture or miscellaneous collection; an olio. B. Jonson.
An arboreal anthropoid ape (Simia satyrus), which inhabits Borneo and Sumatra. Often called simply orang. [Written also orang- outan, orang-utan, ourang-utang, and oran-utan.]
An outer garment.
A green membranous seaweed (Ulva) often found growing on oysters but common on stones, piles, etc.
A hard and strong substance made of a pulp from paper, mixed with sise or glue, etc. It is formed into various articles, usually by means of molds.
Blocks of stone or concrete heaped loosely in the water to make a foundation (as for a sea wall), a mole, etc.
Boar hunting; -- so called by Anglo-Indians. [Colloq.] Tackeray.
See under Pillow.
A bag pudding; a name of reproach or ridicule formerly applied by the Scotch to the English.
A small stick or rod of steel, formerly used in adjusting the plaits of ruffs. Shak.
That part of a crustacean behind the cephalothorax; -- more commonly called abdomen.

A captain of a war vessel whose name appeared, or was "posted," in the seniority list of the British navy, as distinguished from a commander whose name was not so posted. The term was also used in the United States navy; but no such commission as post-captain was ever recognized in either service, and the term has fallen into disuse.
A voter in certain boroughs of England, where, before the passage of the reform bill of 1832, the qualification for suffrage was to have boiled (walloped) his own pot in the parish for six months.
One who cleans pots; a scullion. [Slang, U. S.]
The breaking of a public pound for releasing impounded animals. Blackstone.
The false china root, a plant of the genus Smilax (S. Pseudo- china), found in America.
Any contractile vessel of invertebrates which is not of the nature of a real heart, especially one of those pertaining to the excretory system.
That part of the upper deck abaft the mainmast, including the poop deck when there is one.
A fine quality of sailcloth. Ham. Nav. Encyc.
The act of forming anew; a second forming in order; as, the reformation of a column of troops into a hollow square.
A kind of rural festival at the dedication of a church, when the parishioners brought rushes to strew the church. [Eng.] Nares.
That which gives a safe, passage; either
a convoy or guard to protect a person in an enemy's country or a foreign country, or
a writing, pass, or warrant of security, given to a person to enable him to travel with safety. Shak.
The act of keeping or preserving in safety from injury or from escape; care; custody.
See Saundersblue.

A fellow without breeches; a ragged fellow; -- a name of reproach given in the first French revolution to the extreme republican party, who rejected breeches as an emblem peculiar to the upper classes or aristocracy, and adopted pantaloons.
Hence, an extreme or radical republican; a violent revolutionist; a Jacobin.
A tool for turning screws so as to drive them into their place. It has a thin end which enters the nick in the head of the screw.

The power of discerning what is not visible to the physical eye, or of foreseeing future events, esp. such as are of a disastrous kind; the capacity of a seer; prophetic vision. he was seized with a fit of second-sight. Addison. Nor less availed his optic sleight, And Scottish gift of second- sight. Trumbull.
One's own affairs; one's private business. [Obs.] Shak.
Self-love. [Obs.] Shak.
Control over one's own feelings, temper, etc.; self-control.
Self-communion. [R.]
Conceit of one's self; an overweening opinion of one's powers or endowments.
Concern for one's self.
Control of one's self; restraint exercised over one's self; self-command.
Culture, training, or education of one's self by one's own efforts.
See Self-defense.

The act of defending one's own person, property, or reputation. In self-defense (Law), in protection of self, -- it being permitted in law to a party on whom a grave wrong is attempted to resist the wrong, even at the peril of the life of the assailiant. Wharton.
Opinion, especially high opinion, of one's self; an overweening estimate of one's self or of one's own opinion. Collier.
The act of reproving one's self; censure of one's conduct by one's own judgment.
Respect for one's self; regard for one's character; laudable self-esteem.
The act or habit of seeking one's own interest or happiness; selfishness.

A mechanism (usually one operated by electricity, compressed air, a spring, or an explosive gas), attached to an internal- combustion engine, as on an automobile, and used as a means of starting the engine without cranking it by hand.
The act of inflicting pain on one's self; pain inflicted on one's self.
The idolizing of one's self; immoderate self-conceit.
A naval vessel carrying seventy-four guns.
A printer's tool consisting of a metal bar formed into a hammer head at one end and a claw at the other, -- used as a lever and hammer.
The act of seeing sights; eagerness for novelties or curiosities.

The Guinea-hen flower; -- so called in England because its spotted petals resemble the scales of a snake's head. Dr. Prior. Snake's-head iris (Bot.), an iridaceous plant (Hermodactylus tuberosus) of the Mediterranean region. The flowers slightly resemble a serpent's open mouth.
Soup made chiefly from vegetables or fish with a little butter and a few condiments.
The common yellow water lily (Nuphar advena).
The common American bittern (Botaurus lentiginosus); -- so called because one of its notes resembles the sound made in driving a stake into the mud. Called also meadow hen, and Indian hen.

An ancient high court exercising jurisdiction in certain cases, mainly criminal, which sat without the intervention of a jury. It consisted of the king's council, or of the privy council only with the addition of certain judges. It could proceed on mere rumor or examine witnesses; it could apply torture. It was abolished by the Long Parliament in 1641. Encyc. Brit.

A method adopted in etching, to keep the acid from those parts which are already sufficiently corroded, by applying varnish or other covering matter with a brush, but allowing the acid to act on the other parts.
One who tells stories; a narrator of anecdotes,incidents, or fictitious tales; as, an amusing story-teller.
An historian; -- in contempt. Swift.
A euphemism or child's word for "a liar."
One who writes short stories, as for magazines.
An historian; a chronicler. [Obs.] "Rathums, the story-writer." 1 Esdr. ii. 17.
An instrument to cut straw for fodder.
An acid. [Obs.]
Distilled or ardent spirits; intoxicating liquor.
A corruption of Swan-upping. [Eng.] Encyc. Brit.
A plow for turning up grass land.
A lawn mower.
The horizontal bracing of a bridge, which prevents its swaying.
One who has the actual possession of land; the occupant. [Written also ter-tenant.]
A work thrown up at the end of a bridge nearest the enemy, for covering the communications across a river; a bridgehead.
A vessel of war carrying guns on three decks.
See Tierce, 4.
A name given to some species of morning-glory (Ipomoea) having the leaves lobed in pedate fashion.
A tiring-room. [Obs.] Shak.
Any species of Lingula.
The act or practice of drining the surface of land.
The act of applying a dressing of manure to the surface of land; also, manure so applied.
See Impatiens.
Squirting cucumber. See under Cucumber.

A small bar of gold and silver, either pure, or alloyed in some known proportion with copper, for trying the purity of articles of gold or silver by comparison of the streaks made by the article and the bar on a touchstone.

A kind of drama representing some action in which serious and comic scenes are blended; a composition partaking of the nature both of tragedy and comedy. The noble tragi-comedy of "Measure for Measure." Macaulay.
Spurge nettle. See under Nettle.
A feeder; a great eater; a gormandizer. Shak.
A cook. [Obs.] The skillfulest trencher-men of Media. Sir P. Sidney.
A table companion; a trencher mate. Thackeray.
A pit in the form of an inverted cone or pyramid, constructed as an obstacle to the approach of an enemy, and having a pointed stake in the middle. The pits are called also trapholes.
Any bivalve shell of the genus Mactra. See Mactra.
One who tells the truth. Truth-teller was our England's Alfred named. Tennyson.
A sea urchin when deprived of its spines; -- popularly so called from a fancied resemblance to a turban.
Any one of several large, thick, spiral marine shells belonging to Rapa and allied genera, somewhat turnip-shaped.
The turtle cowrie.
A confection of different kinds of preserved fruits. -- a.
Flavored with, or containing, various fruits.
An ornamented cake distributed among friends or visitors on the festival of Twelfth-night.
An avant-courier. See Van-courier. [Obs.] Holland.
The constellation Aquarius.
A privy; especially, a privy furnished with a contrivance for introducing a stream of water to cleanse it.
A kind of implement used for tearing up weeds esp. on summer fallows. [Prov. Eng.]
Same as Whitlow grass, under Whitlow.
One who courts widows, seeking to marry one with a fortune. Addison.
A thorny European shrub (Hippophaë rhamnoides) resembling a willow.
A vicious habit of a horse, consisting in the swallowing of air; -- usually associated with crib-biting, or cribbing. See Cribbing, 4.
The act of pulling the wires, as of a puppet; hence, secret influence or management, especially in politics; intrigue.
One who cavils at words.
A marine shell of the genus Turbo. See Turbo.
A person appointed by law to take charge of goods, etc., thrown on shore after a shipwreck.
A certain plant, probably the yellow oxeye. B. Jonson.
A mineral of a violet-blue color, inclining to gray and white. It is a hydrous fluoride of cerium, yttrium, and calcium.
A kind of water found in copper mines; water impregnated with copper.
Divination by means of barley meal. Knowles.
Opposition to, or hatred of, Semites, esp. Jews. -- An`ti- Sem"ite (#), n. -- An`ti-Sem*it"ic (#), a.
A person dispatched before another person or company, to give notice of his or their approach.
Same as Bas-relief.
1. (Mil.) An engine used in ancient times to beat down the walls of besieged places.
A blacksmith's hammer, suspended, and worked horizontally.
See Acanthus, n., 1.
The English cow parsnip (Heracleum sphondylium) Dr. Prior.
Idle talk; babble. Shak.
The knotgrass (Polygonum aviculare).
An umbelliferous plant of the genus Ammi.
Goutweed (Ægopodium podagraria).
Wood betony (Stachys betonica); also, the plant called fennel flower (Nigella Damascena), or devil-in-a-bush.
A key or other device for breaking an electrical circuit.
The lyre bird.
See Bull's-eye, 3.
A kind of candy, mainly composed of sugar and butter. [Colloq.] Dickens.
An appendage; that which depends on something else, or is distinct from the main dependence; an accessory. Shak.
The kiling of another in self-defense upon a sudden and unpremeditated encounter. See Chaud-Medley.
Luck; chance; accident. Milton. Cowper.
A masterpiece; a capital work in art, literature, etc.
A decorative construction around the opning of a fireplace.
See under Cloud.
See under Cloud.
See Chiaroscuro.
See Chiaroscuro.
Spice clove. [Obs.] Chaucer.
One who is compos mentis. [Colloq.]
A kind of spiral curve found in certain univalve shells. Agassiz.
Nicolite.
One who is called upon to answer a summons or other proceeding jointly with another.
See Contradance. He had introduced the English country-dance to the knowledge of the Dutch ladies. Macualay.
One who makes it his business to marry beggars to each other. Swift.
A court consisting of military or naval officers, for the trial of one belonging to the army or navy, or of offenses against military or naval law.
Sticking plaster made by coating taffeta or silk on one side with some adhesive substance, commonly a mixture of isinglass and glycerin.
A first cousin. See Note under Cousin, 1.
A throw in which the wrestler turns his left side to his opponent, places his left leg across both legs of his opponent, and pulls him forward over his hip; hence, an unexpected defeat or repulse.
A counter or opposing purpose; hence, that which is inconsistent or contradictory. Shaftesbury.

A conversational game, in which questions and answers are made so as to involve ludicrous combinations of ideas. Pepys. To be at cross-purposes, to misunderstand or to act counter to one another without intending it; -- said of persons.
The reading of the lines of a newspaper directly across the page, instead of down the columns, thus producing a ludicrous combination of ideas.
Reckless mischief; the action of a dare-devil.
A plant (Liatris odoratissima) whose fleshy leaves give out a fragrance compared to vanilla. Wood.
Inactivity; habitual sloth; idleness. [Jocular] Carlyle. Miss Austen.
A man-of-war having two gun decks.
A public conveyance, as a street car, with seats on the roof. [Colloq.]
A kind of coasting sled, made of two sleds fastened together with a board, one before the other. [Local, U. S.]
Deceit; duplicity. Now cometh the sin of double-tongue, such as speak fair before folk and wickedly behind. Chaucer.
One of several pieces fayed across the apron and lapped in the knightheads, or inside planking above the upper deck. Ham. Nav. Encyc.
Motion excited by reflex nerves. See Excito-motory.
The father of one's husband or wife; -- correlative to son-in- law and daughter-in-law.
A European marine fish (Cottus bubalis), allied to the sculpin; -- called also lucky proach.
The act of finding fault or blaming; -- used derogatively. Also Adj.
A trifle; trifling talk; nonsense. [Colloq.] Spectator.
A trifle. [Low] Hudibras.
A chisel, thin in proportion to its width. It has a tang to enter the handle instead of a socket for receiving it. Knight.
Five-twenty bonds of the United States (bearing six per cent interest), issued in 1862, '64, and '65, redeemable after five and payable in twenty years.
A species of amaranth (Amarantus melancholicus).
Foolish expenditure; waste. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A small herb, of the genus Myosotis (M. palustris, incespitosa, etc.), bearing a beautiful blue flower, and extensively considered the emblem of fidelity.
An agent exciting secretion of milk.
A mixture of two malt liquors, esp. porter and ale, in about equal parts. Dickens.
Professional cant; the chatter of conjurers to divert attention from their tricks; hence, jugglery. [Colloq.]
Having coarse, unattractive or stern features. Smollett.
Direct, forcible, and effective speaking. Milton.
An old term for blindman's buff. Shak.
A tobacco pipe, so arranged that the smoke passes through water, making a bubbling noise, whence its name. In India, the bulb containing the water is often a cocoanut shell.
Privacy; secrecy. Commonly in the phrase in hugger-mugger, with haste and secrecy. [Archaic] Many things have been done in hugger-mugger. Fuller.
A rich, powerful, perfume, obtained from the volatile oil of the flowers of Canada odorata, an East Indian tree. [Also written ylang-ylang.]
A professional builder who erects cheap dwellings of poor materials and unsubstantial and slovenly construction.
That which is restless and uneasy.
A wandering knight; a knight who traveled in search of adventures, for the purpose of exhibiting military skill, prowess, and generosity.
An old tune of a dance, the name of which made it a proverbial expression of levity, especially in love matters. Nares. "Best sing it to the tune of light-o'-love." Shak.
Hence: A light or wanton woman. Beau. & Fl.
A bank or a pawnbroker's shop.
A public institution for lending money to the poor at a moderate interest, upon articles deposited and pledged; -- called also mont de piété.
A mirror made of glass on which has been placed a backing of some reflecting substance, as quicksilver. There is none so homely but loves a looking-glass. South.
The state of being love-sick.
The principles of the low-church party.
One who holds low-church principles.
A kind of large field beet (B. macrorhiza), used as food for cattle, -- by some considered a mere variety of the ordinary beet. See Beet. [Written also mangold-wurzel.]
Mezzo-rilievo.
A middle degree of relief in figures, between high and low relief.
Sculpture in this kind of relief. See under Alto-rilievo.
The part of geology relating to structure and organisms which require to be studied with a microscope.
That part of a picture between the foreground and the background.
A milled sixpence; -- the sixpence being one of the first English coins milled (1561).
A hotchpotch. [Obs.] Latimer.
A climbing plant (Ipomoea purpurea) having handsome, funnel- shaped flowers, usually red, pink, purple, white, or variegated, sometimes pale blue. See Dextrorsal.
The mother of one's husband or wife.
A firearm which receives its charge through the muzzle, as distinguished from one which is loaded at the breech.
A person who never does, or fares, well; a good for nothing.

The theory which holds natural selection, as explained by Darwin, to be the chief factor in the evolution of plants and animals, and denies the inheritance of acquired characters; -- esp. opposed to Neo-Lamarckism. Weismannism is an example of extreme Neo- Darwinism. -- Ne`o-Dar*win"i*an, a. & n.
Hellenism as surviving or revival in modern times; the practice or pursuit of ancient Greek ideals in modern life, art, or literature, as in the Renaissance.
A circular or oval window; -- generally used of architecture of the 17th and 18th centuries. A famous room in the palace of Versailles bears this name, from the oval window opening into it.
See Orang-outang.
The glory pea. See under Glory.
One who furnishes matter to public journals at so much a line; a poor writer for hire; a hack writer. Thackeray.
A photo-engraving produced by any process involving the etching of the plate.
See Pilgarlic.
A sound like that of alternating light beats. Also, a pattering of words.
Same as Poly, n.
The closely related Teucrium montanum, formerly called Polium montanum, a plant of Southern Europe.
The Bartsia alpina, a low purple-flowered herb of Europe.

A large doorway allowing vehicles to drive into or through a building. It is common to have the entrance door open upon the passage of the porte-cochère. Also, a porch over a driveway before an entrance door.

One of the dwellers in the Cistercian convent of Port Royal des Champs, near Paris, when it was the home of the Jansenists in the 17th century, among them being Arnauld, Pascal, and other famous scholars. Cf. Jansenist.
A hydrocarbon of the aromatic series, metameric with mesitylene and cumene, found in coal tar, and obtained as a colorless liquid.
False galena, or blende. See Blende (a).
A cousin within the first four degrees of kindred.
One who has an estate after a particular estate is determined. See Remainder, n., 3. Blackstone.
A chair mounted on rockers, in which one may rock.
The figure of a horse, mounted upon rockers, for children to ride.
A stone, often of great size and weight, resting upon another stone, and so exactly poised that it can be rocked, or slightly moved, with but little force.
A kind of color prepared from calcined lapis lazuli; ultramarine; also, a blue prepared from carbonate of copper. [Written also sanders-blue.]
A giddy or thoughtless person; one incapable of concentration or attention. [Written also scatter-brains.]
Hopscotch.
The quality or state of being self-active; self-action.
Applause of one's self.
Accusation of one's self. [R.] Milman.
The act of deluding one's self, or the state of being thus deluded.
The act of devoting one's self, or the state of being self- devoted; willingness to sacrifice one's own advantage or happiness for the sake of others; self-sacrifice.
Want of confidence in one' self; diffidence.
The quality or state of being self-evident. Locke.
The act of exposing one's self; the state of being so exposed.
The act of killing one's self; suicide. Hakewill.
Private interest; the interest or advantage of one's self.
A suicide.
Reliance on one's own powers or judgment; self-trust.
The act of reproaching one's self; censure by one's own conscience.
The doctrines or tenets of the Semi-Arians.

A follower of John Cassianus, a French monk (died about 448), who modified the doctrines of Pelagius, by denying human merit, and maintaining the necessity of the Spirit's influence, while, on the other hand, he rejected the Augustinian doctrines of election, the inability of man to do good, and the certain perseverance of the saints.
The treatment of disease by the injection of blood serum from immune animals.
A firearm, esp. a pistol, with seven barrels or chambers for cartridges, or one capable of firing seven shots without reloading. [Colloq.]
One who shears, or cuts off the wool from, sheep.
One who, or that which, carries a shield.
Any small moth of the genus Aspidisca, whose larva makes a shieldlike covering for itself out of bits of leaves.
Irresolution; hesitation; also, occupation with trifles. She lost not one of her forty-five minutes in picking and choosing, - - no shilly-shally in Kate. De Quincey.
The sister of one's husband or wife; also, the wife of one's brother; sometimes, the wife of one's husband's or wife's brother.
One who uses abusive slang; a ranting partisan. [Colloq. or Humorous] W. Irving.
A plant (Tragopogon pratensis) which closes its flowers at midday; a kind of goat's beard. Dr. Prior.
The American white-fronted goose (Anser albifrons).
Adultery. [Obs.]
The line which forms the communication between the steering wheel and the telltale.
A curious paradise bird (Semioptera Wallacii) which has two long special feathers standing erect on each wing.
The men in the starboard watch. [Obs.] R. H. Dana, Jr.
A steamboat having a stern wheel instead of side wheels. [Colloq. U.S.]
A dress of strong materials for restraining maniacs or those who are violently delirious. It has long sleeves, which are closed at the ends, confining the hands, and may be tied behind the back.
An alto-stratus cloud.
Water for the cure of surfeits. [Obs.] Locke.
A kind of Scotch cap of wool, worsted, or the like, having a round, flattish top much wider than the band which fits the head, and usually having a tassel in the center.

A station on the Nile, midway between Thebes and Memphis, forming the site of the capital of Amenophis IV., whose archive chamber was discovered there in 1887. A collection of tablets (called the Tel-el-Amarna, or the Amarna, tablets) was found here, forming the Asiatic correspondence (Tel-el-Amarna letters) of Amenophis IV. and his father, Amenophis III., written in cuneiform characters. It is an important source of our knowledge of Asia from about 1400 to 1370 b. c..
A certain game of children; seesaw; -- called also titter- totter, and titter-cum-totter.
An under constable. Shak. Johnson.
Idle, trifling talk; empty prattle. Arbuthnot.
An idle, trifling talker; a gossip. [R.] Tatler.

A kind of starch with very large, oval, flattened grains, often sold as arrowroot, and extensively used for adulterating cocoa. It is made from the rootstocks of a species of Canna, probably C. edulis, the tubers of which are edible every month in the year.
All together; hence, in costume, the fine arts, etc., the general effect of a work as a whole, without regard to the execution of the separate perts.
A member of any race of the Turko-Iranian type.
The evening of Epiphany, or the twelfth day after Christmas, observed as a festival by various churches.
A garment worn below another.
See Van-courier. [Obs.] Shak.
One who performs wonders, or miracles.

A process in photographic printing, in which a relief pattern in gelatin, which has been hardened after certain operations, is pressed upon a plate of lead or other soft metal. An intaglio impression in thus produced, from which pictures may be directly printed, but by a slower process than in common printing.
A print from such a plate.
The name of a tune adopted popularly as one of the national airs of the United States.
Humorously, a Yankee. We might have withheld our political noodles From knocking their heads against hot Yankee-Doodles. Moore.
A genus of ferns (Ophioglossum), whose seeds are produced on a spike resembling a serpent's tongue.
The yellow dogtooth violet. Gray.
The quality of being advisable or expedient; expediency; advisability.
A member of the Church of England who contends for its catholic character; more specifically, a High Churchman.
The Anglo-Saxon domain (i. e., Great Britain and the United States, etc.); the Anglo-Saxon race.
A characteristic of the Anglo-Saxon race; especially, a word or an idiom of the Anglo-Saxon tongue. M. Arnold.
The quality or sentiment of being Anglo-Saxon, or English in its ethnological sense.
Poisoning caused by a virus that originates and develops in the organism itself.
A mineral of a white or gray color, occurring massive or crystallized. It is a compound of the carbonates of barium and calcium.
One versed in belleslettres.
Polite or elegant literature; the humanities; -- used somewhat vaguely for literary works in which imagination and taste are predominant.
Hunting for, or taking, birds' nests or their contents.
The brother of one's husband or wife; also, the husband of one's sister; sometimes, the husband of one's wife's sister.
A remedy that purges by alvine discharges.
The horizontal projection of a chimney from the wall in which it is built; -- commonly applied to its projection in the inside of a building only.

One of several prickly or thorny shrubs found in Palestine, especially the Paliurus aculeatus, Zizyphus Spina-Christi, and Z. vulgaris. The last bears the fruit called jujube, and may be considered to have been the most readily obtainable for the Crown of Thorns.
One of the same religion with another.
A movable sideboard or buffet, on which plate and other articles of luxury were displayed on special ocasions. [Obs.] A way with the joint stools, remove the court-cupboard, look to the plate. Shak.
See Christcross-row.
A cross having the three upper ends crossed, so as to from three small crosses.
One who cross-examines or conducts a crosse-examination.
One of the ribs in a groined arch, springing from the corners in a diagonal direction.
Vaulting formed by the intersection of two or more simple vaults.
A spring-blooming plant (Fritillaria imperialis) of the Lily family, having at the top of the stalk a cluster of pendent bell- shaped flowers surmounted with a tuft of green leaves.
A bulkhead on the forecastle and half deck of a ship.
See under Dead, a.

A mass, usually of soft iron, but sometimes of some other magnetic metal, as nickel or cobalt, rendered temporarily magnetic by being placed within a coil of wire through which a current of electricity is passing. The metal is generally in the form of a bar, either straight, or bent into the shape of a horseshoe.
The motion of electricity or its passage from one metal to another in a voltaic circuit; mechanical action produced by means of electricity.
One who studies the fashions; a fop; a dandy. Marston.
Sympathy; a like feeling.
Joint interest. [Obs.] Arbuthnot.

Concrete strengthened by a core or foundation skeleton of iron or steel bars, strips, etc. Floors, columns, piles, water pipes, etc., have been successfully made of it. Called also armored concrete steel, and reënforced concrete.
A genus of perennial herbs (Iris) with swordlike leaves and large three-petaled flowers often of very gay colors, but probably white in the plant first chosen for the royal French emblem.

A certain tenure in tail special; an estate of inheritance given to a man his wife (the wife being of the blood of the donor), and descendible to the heirs of their two bodies begotten. [Obs.] Blackstone.
See Falcon-gentil.
A small, strong carriage for conveying materials on a railroad. [Eng.]
A son of one's grandson or granddaughter.
The native language of the Irish; that branch of the Celtic languages spoken by the natives of Ireland. Also adj.
The principles of the high-church party.
